in Switzerland as an expat.

00:00:42.208 --> 00:00:45.136
Diccon has been living in
Switzerland for eight years

00:00:45.136 --> 00:00:48.560
and has written three books in
that time about the culture

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:50.124
that we live in.

00:00:50.124 --> 00:00:52.900
He has a history in writing
and books, having been a

00:00:52.900 --> 00:00:55.590
travel writer for 10 years in
the UK before his move,

00:00:55.590 --> 00:00:57.367
followed by five years
of managing the

00:00:57.367 --> 00:00:59.920
English bookshop in Bern.

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:01.975
Tonight, he'll be sharing from
his bestselling book, "Swiss

00:01:01.975 --> 00:01:03.690
Watching," which was
a "Financial

00:01:03.690 --> 00:01:05.140
Times" Book of the Year.

00:01:05.140 --> 00:01:07.550
Please join me in a warm welcome
for Diccon Bewes.

00:01:07.550 --> 00:01:14.795
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:14.795 --> 00:01:16.250
DICCON BEWES: Thank
you very much.

00:01:16.250 --> 00:01:17.260
Thank you for inviting me.

00:01:17.260 --> 00:01:18.610
It's great to be here.

00:01:18.610 --> 00:01:21.115
My first time at Google,
although, of course, I use

00:01:21.115 --> 00:01:22.490
Google an awful lot.

00:01:22.490 --> 00:01:27.250
The books wouldn't exist without
it, although I do do

00:01:27.250 --> 00:01:31.060
real research, as well, in a
library, not just online.

00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:33.150
I am an author and a bookseller,
so I like real

00:01:33.150 --> 00:01:35.240
books as well.

00:01:35.240 --> 00:01:38.325
Today, I'm going to talk about
what it feels like

00:01:38.325 --> 00:01:39.685
for me to live here.

00:01:39.685 --> 00:01:41.325
I've been here eight years.

00:01:41.325 --> 00:01:45.675
I didn't speak German when
I arrived, and I

00:01:45.675 --> 00:01:46.670
knew some Swiss people.

00:01:46.670 --> 00:01:48.430
My boyfriend is Swiss.

00:01:48.430 --> 00:01:51.770
But I was kind of thrown
in at the deep end.

00:01:51.770 --> 00:01:54.290
And I'd like to talk about
what it feels like to be

00:01:54.290 --> 00:01:58.200
living in the land of
milk and money.

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:03.110
So that's just a bit about me to
show you there is a reason

00:02:03.110 --> 00:02:05.060
why I am here.

00:02:05.060 --> 00:02:08.850
And I'd like to start by talking
about this made up

00:02:08.850 --> 00:02:13.450
word called "Swissness." It's
a word the Swiss invented to

00:02:13.450 --> 00:02:15.240
describe how they feel
about themselves.

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:18.545
It looks like an English word,
and you can kind of guess the

00:02:18.545 --> 00:02:20.730
meaning if you're an
English speaker.

00:02:20.730 --> 00:02:22.740
But it doesn't really exist.

00:02:22.740 --> 00:02:27.590
It's a bit like another
Swissness word, "wellness,"

00:02:27.590 --> 00:02:29.580
which isn't the opposite
of illness.

00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:30.760
It's actually a nice thing.

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:32.760
It's you go to a spa
for a weekend.

00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:35.380
But if you say "wellness" in
England, most people won't

00:02:35.380 --> 00:02:36.290
know what you mean.

00:02:36.290 --> 00:02:39.460
And wellness in America is
something medical, definitely

00:02:39.460 --> 00:02:41.850
not something enjoyable.

00:02:41.850 --> 00:02:44.972
So I'd like to take each letter
of Swissness to try and

00:02:44.972 --> 00:02:48.560
explain what it means to me.

00:02:48.560 --> 00:02:53.430
So the first S is for shells,
which might seem a bit

00:02:53.430 --> 00:02:56.960
strange, given that we're
a long way from the sea.

00:02:56.960 --> 00:02:58.760
In the book, I call Switzerland
the landlocked

00:02:58.760 --> 00:03:02.850
island because it has this
island mentality, being in the

00:03:02.850 --> 00:03:06.640
center of Europe, but not
really part of it.

00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:09.100
But this is a very special
sort of shell, and

00:03:09.100 --> 00:03:10.350
I brought one along.

00:03:15.950 --> 00:03:20.990
Now, you all think this is
a coconut, but it's not.

00:03:20.990 --> 00:03:22.660
It looks like a coconut,
I know.

00:03:22.660 --> 00:03:23.485
And it feels like a coconut.

00:03:23.485 --> 00:03:25.782
But it is, in fact,
a Swiss person.

00:03:29.560 --> 00:03:31.960
And that doesn't mean that I'm
saying all Swiss people are

00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:33.970
small, brown, and hairy--

00:03:33.970 --> 00:03:35.960
although some are, I'm sure--

00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:38.550
or that you want to throw things
at them all the time.

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:42.090
It means that they have a
very hard outer shell.

00:03:42.090 --> 00:03:44.340
So it's quite hard to
get to know a Swiss

00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:47.420
person easily or properly.

00:03:47.420 --> 00:03:51.565
And it's because the hard outer
shell protects their

00:03:51.565 --> 00:03:53.030
private sphere.

00:03:53.030 --> 00:03:54.620
So in Switzerland, it's
very normal to

00:03:54.620 --> 00:03:57.480
separate public from private.

00:03:57.480 --> 00:04:02.360
And when you arrive here, as an
English speaker especially,

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:05.310
the coconut can feel a little
bit cold, a little bit

00:04:05.310 --> 00:04:07.650
unfriendly, a little
bit distant.

00:04:07.650 --> 00:04:10.400
But what it actually is is
respecting your privacy,

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:13.830
respecting your private sphere,
and taking time to get

00:04:13.830 --> 00:04:17.925
to know you, taking time to
let you into their shell.

00:04:17.925 --> 00:04:21.810
Now, sometimes it can happen
quite quickly, especially if

00:04:21.810 --> 00:04:24.280
you're dealing with a
Swiss person who's

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:25.180
lived abroad, for instance.

00:04:25.180 --> 00:04:28.720
But other times, it can happen
very, very slowly, because

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:30.576
once a Swiss person
calls you their

00:04:30.576 --> 00:04:32.825
friend, it means something.

00:04:32.825 --> 00:04:35.010
A friend here is a friend
for life, not

00:04:35.010 --> 00:04:36.500
just a friend on Facebook.

00:04:36.500 --> 00:04:38.063
It actually means something.

00:04:38.063 --> 00:04:42.240
So they take their time
to call you a friend.

00:04:42.240 --> 00:04:45.020
So for example, I go swimming
two, three times a week at an

00:04:45.020 --> 00:04:47.590
indoor pool in Bern.

00:04:47.590 --> 00:04:51.480
And if you go the same time,
same day, over and over again,

00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:53.860
you see the same faces.

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:55.900
And if you're an ignorant
foreigner, you say hello to

00:04:55.900 --> 00:04:57.150
these people you don't
know, because you

00:04:57.150 --> 00:04:58.350
recognize their faces.

00:04:58.350 --> 00:05:00.644
And then about three years
later, they say hello back.

00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:07.730
English-speaking societies--

00:05:07.730 --> 00:05:09.400
and this isn't my idea.

00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:10.620
It's been around for
a long time.

00:05:10.620 --> 00:05:13.700
The classifying of societies
as coconuts, or

00:05:13.700 --> 00:05:16.680
English-speaking societies
are peaches, typically.

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:18.775
And that's the soft
outer flesh.

00:05:18.775 --> 00:05:20.990
It's quite easy to get
toknow someone.

00:05:20.990 --> 00:05:25.315
You can be chatting to someone
at a bus stop, and you've

00:05:25.315 --> 00:05:27.570
swapped mobile phone
numbers by the end.

00:05:27.570 --> 00:05:28.435
The outer flesh--

00:05:28.435 --> 00:05:31.510
every stranger is a potential
friend, rather than a

00:05:31.510 --> 00:05:34.710
potential enemy, not
to be let in.

00:05:34.710 --> 00:05:36.695
But it can feel a
bit superficial.

00:05:36.695 --> 00:05:39.210
It can feel like you go straight
through to the flesh,

00:05:39.210 --> 00:05:40.830
and you don't really
know anyone.

00:05:40.830 --> 00:05:45.110
And it's the hard inner core
which is really the bit that

00:05:45.110 --> 00:05:45.880
is protected.

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:48.150
So your very close family.

00:05:48.150 --> 00:05:51.260
So it's the reverse
of a coconut.

00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:54.390
And the trouble with being a
peach in the land of coconuts

00:05:54.390 --> 00:05:57.320
is you can get very bruised
a lot of the time.

00:05:57.320 --> 00:05:59.810
And so I get a lot of emails
from expats living here

00:05:59.810 --> 00:06:04.500
saying, now I understand why my
neighbors are polite, but

00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:06.396
in three years, they've never
invited me around

00:06:06.396 --> 00:06:08.270
for a cup of coffee.

00:06:08.270 --> 00:06:09.530
It's not that they're
unfriendly.

00:06:09.530 --> 00:06:12.960
It's just they're very formal
and a little bit distant.

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:16.840
So it's all about respecting
boundaries.

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:18.690
W is for weather.

00:06:21.754 --> 00:06:25.590
British people love to talk
about the weather.

00:06:25.590 --> 00:06:27.450
It's our main topic
of conversation.

00:06:27.450 --> 00:06:30.416
When all else fails, talk
about the weather.

00:06:30.416 --> 00:06:35.390
In Switzerland, it's not such a
great opener with people you

00:06:35.390 --> 00:06:35.660
don't know.

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:37.480
In private, the weather
is a topic.

00:06:37.480 --> 00:06:41.090
But using the weather to start
a conversation or to get to

00:06:41.090 --> 00:06:44.030
know someone is kind of
illogical for Swiss people,

00:06:44.030 --> 00:06:46.370
because it's not really
worth talking about.

00:06:46.370 --> 00:06:48.760
This is a typical British-Swiss
weather

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:49.720
conversation.

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:52.111
I would come in from outside
and say, oh, it's cold out

00:06:52.111 --> 00:06:53.770
there today.

00:06:53.770 --> 00:06:55.300
And the Swiss person would
say, well, it's winter.

00:07:00.360 --> 00:07:03.320
And that's because for
me, that's the start.

00:07:03.320 --> 00:07:05.630
I'd say, I know, but did you
see, it's going to be 19

00:07:05.630 --> 00:07:07.280
degrees at the weekend,
or it was even worse

00:07:07.280 --> 00:07:09.090
this time last year.

00:07:09.090 --> 00:07:09.860
It was minus 30.

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:11.540
And then we would have a
conversation about the

00:07:11.540 --> 00:07:14.800
weather, and it lead to other
things, even if I didn't know

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:15.670
that person.

00:07:15.670 --> 00:07:19.620
Whereas for the Swiss person,
I've stated the obvious.

00:07:19.620 --> 00:07:20.520
It's cold.

00:07:20.520 --> 00:07:21.660
So therefore, they state
the obvious.

00:07:21.660 --> 00:07:22.510
It's winter.

00:07:22.510 --> 00:07:24.840
And that's actually the end
of the conversation.

00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:27.370
It's not the start of
the conversation.

00:07:27.370 --> 00:07:31.670
So it can feel like getting
through this coconut shell

00:07:31.670 --> 00:07:34.567
with small talk is like banging
your head against a

00:07:34.567 --> 00:07:36.090
brick wall.

00:07:36.090 --> 00:07:40.630
And mainly because small talk
here is about this big.

00:07:40.630 --> 00:07:45.350
And it's partly to do with a lot
of small-talk topics are

00:07:45.350 --> 00:07:49.210
too invasive of someone's
shell.

00:07:49.210 --> 00:07:50.990
So you don't ask someone's
marital status.

00:07:50.990 --> 00:07:52.860
You don't ask if they
have children.

00:07:52.860 --> 00:07:55.880
You certainly don't talk about
the price of your house, all

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:58.270
of which are perfectly
normal topics of

00:07:58.270 --> 00:08:00.371
conversation in Britain.

00:08:00.371 --> 00:08:03.055
Partly, here, because almost
everyone rents, but partly

00:08:03.055 --> 00:08:05.035
because it's much
too personal.

00:08:05.035 --> 00:08:09.540
And to become too personal too
quickly is to invade someone's

00:08:09.540 --> 00:08:10.880
private sphere.

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:14.710
So you have to remember, it's
not being unfriendly.

00:08:14.710 --> 00:08:17.920
It's just getting to know you
in a Swiss fashion, which

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:19.390
takes a little bit longer.

00:08:19.390 --> 00:08:20.270
Baby steps.

00:08:20.270 --> 00:08:22.670
The small talk needs
baby steps.

00:08:22.670 --> 00:08:27.698
And the most important thing
is remember the humor is a

00:08:27.698 --> 00:08:30.911
private thing, generally,
in Switzerland.

00:08:30.911 --> 00:08:32.520
It's a bit like sex and money.

00:08:32.520 --> 00:08:36.600
It doesn't appear in
public very often.

00:08:36.600 --> 00:08:38.100
You can tell jokes with
your friends.

00:08:38.100 --> 00:08:39.520
You can tell jokes
with your family.

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:42.740
But in a business environment,
especially with people you

00:08:42.740 --> 00:08:46.070
don't know, then it implies that
you're not taking that

00:08:46.070 --> 00:08:46.750
meeting seriously.

00:08:46.750 --> 00:08:50.380
If you start the meeting with a
joke or a funny story about

00:08:50.380 --> 00:08:53.125
something that happened on your
way to the meeting, then

00:08:53.125 --> 00:08:55.570
very often, a lot of the Swiss
people will look at you and

00:08:55.570 --> 00:08:57.810
thinking, well, are you here
for business or pleasure?

00:08:57.810 --> 00:09:03.040
Because you're not respecting
the boundaries.

00:09:03.040 --> 00:09:05.330
So be very careful about
using humor.

00:09:05.330 --> 00:09:07.230
Of course, if you're a
foreigner, you get away with

00:09:07.230 --> 00:09:08.270
an awful lot.

00:09:08.270 --> 00:09:10.775
They just think,
oh, foreigner.

00:09:10.775 --> 00:09:15.290
And so you can tell jokes, and
people will laugh politely.

00:09:15.290 --> 00:09:20.380
But it only goes so far.

00:09:20.380 --> 00:09:21.775
And of course, the weather
in Switzerland is

00:09:21.775 --> 00:09:22.630
worth talking about.

00:09:22.630 --> 00:09:24.090
It has great extremes.

00:09:24.090 --> 00:09:25.890
Plus 41 is the highest
temperature.

00:09:25.890 --> 00:09:27.720
Minus 41 is the lowest
temperature.

00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:30.490
So it is often worth
talking about.

00:09:30.490 --> 00:09:31.740
I is for introductions.

00:09:33.990 --> 00:09:38.040
Very important in Switzerland,
because in almost any

00:09:38.040 --> 00:09:42.020
situation, social or business
but especially social, you

00:09:42.020 --> 00:09:44.570
don't do what I did when I went
to my first dinner party

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:45.900
here in Switzerland.

00:09:45.900 --> 00:09:47.255
I didn't really know anyone.

00:09:47.255 --> 00:09:48.280
I knew my boyfriend.

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:49.050
I knew the hosts.

00:09:49.050 --> 00:09:51.900
There were about 30 people
there already.

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:54.500
So I did what any normal English
person would do in

00:09:54.500 --> 00:09:55.150
that situation.

00:09:55.150 --> 00:10:00.340
I went and hid in the corner
and waited for the host to

00:10:00.340 --> 00:10:02.810
take me around and introduce
me or for someone who I

00:10:02.810 --> 00:10:05.580
vaguely recognized
to come over.

00:10:05.580 --> 00:10:08.840
What I certainly would never do
is go up to someone with my

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:10.970
hand out and say,
hi, I'm Diccon.

00:10:10.970 --> 00:10:12.520
For me, as an English
person, that's very

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:16.240
American, very forward.

00:10:16.240 --> 00:10:16.880
Hi, I'm Diccon.

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:18.130
I'm your waiter this evening.

00:10:20.620 --> 00:10:23.710
But for Swiss people, who are
actually quite reserved,

00:10:23.710 --> 00:10:26.940
sitting in their little coconut
shells, one of the few

00:10:26.940 --> 00:10:30.310
times they come out
willingly is when

00:10:30.310 --> 00:10:32.950
they arrive at a party.

00:10:32.950 --> 00:10:34.880
The first thing you're supposed
to do is go around

00:10:34.880 --> 00:10:36.840
and greet everyone who's
already there.

00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:38.700
It takes some time.

00:10:38.700 --> 00:10:40.590
And literally, the first
thing you do, before

00:10:40.590 --> 00:10:42.310
you even have a drink.

00:10:42.310 --> 00:10:44.790
So it can be that if there
were more than 30 people

00:10:44.790 --> 00:10:48.040
there, half an hour later,
you've just about made it

00:10:48.040 --> 00:10:49.885
around the room, and
you're gasping.

00:10:49.885 --> 00:10:54.150
And you're just like, please,
someone get me a drink.

00:10:54.150 --> 00:10:56.670
But it's very important, because
even if you never

00:10:56.670 --> 00:11:00.140
speak to that person the rest of
the evening, you have done

00:11:00.140 --> 00:11:02.380
the polite thing and introduced
yourself.

00:11:02.380 --> 00:11:05.110
And of course, if you know the
person, then you can spend a

00:11:05.110 --> 00:11:06.656
couple minutes chatting.

00:11:06.656 --> 00:11:10.280
But you both know that at some
point, you have to move on,

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:12.510
and you will have
to come back.

00:11:12.510 --> 00:11:15.430
So it's not impolite to then
say, I'm sorry, off and off

00:11:15.430 --> 00:11:17.460
you go doing the round.

00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:22.577
The hard thing is leaving,
because when you leave, you're

00:11:22.577 --> 00:11:25.846
supposed to go around and
say goodbye and remember

00:11:25.846 --> 00:11:28.650
everyone's name.

00:11:28.650 --> 00:11:29.920
And for me, that's
very difficult.

00:11:29.920 --> 00:11:31.935
Very often, I'm the only
foreigner in the room.

00:11:31.935 --> 00:11:35.290
I have a strange name, anyway,
even for English speakers.

00:11:35.290 --> 00:11:38.250
So people remember my
name and my face.

00:11:38.250 --> 00:11:40.420
And so they come along and say,
well, goodbye, Diccon.

00:11:40.420 --> 00:11:44.105
And I'm left, oh, oh,
are you Martin?

00:11:44.105 --> 00:11:45.200
Are you Stefan?

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:48.842
Because nearly every Swiss
man is Martin or Stefan.

00:11:48.842 --> 00:11:50.340
Oh no, you're over 60.

00:11:50.340 --> 00:11:53.350
You must be Hans [INAUDIBLE].

00:11:53.350 --> 00:11:55.580
It's really embarrassing when
you have to ask everyone's

00:11:55.580 --> 00:11:57.140
name over and over again.

00:11:57.140 --> 00:12:00.652
So to get over these two
problems, I have two tips for

00:12:00.652 --> 00:12:02.810
you, which work every time.

00:12:02.810 --> 00:12:04.212
First--

00:12:04.212 --> 00:12:07.810
and this is why all Swiss
people are punctual--

00:12:07.810 --> 00:12:09.060
arrive first.

00:12:11.320 --> 00:12:12.760
Then you stand there.

00:12:12.760 --> 00:12:15.640
You have your drink.

00:12:15.640 --> 00:12:17.640
You can chat with whoever
you want.

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:18.950
You don't have to do anything.

00:12:18.950 --> 00:12:23.260
Everyone else has to do the
round, and you stand there

00:12:23.260 --> 00:12:25.890
relaxed, having fun, enjoying
the evening.

00:12:25.890 --> 00:12:29.710
So there's always that scramble
for the door at one

00:12:29.710 --> 00:12:32.685
minute past 7:00 when everyone's
been told to arrive

00:12:32.685 --> 00:12:34.891
at 7:00, because everyone wants
to be first and not have

00:12:34.891 --> 00:12:37.450
to do this round.

00:12:37.450 --> 00:12:43.370
Secondly, when you leave, wait
until someone else is leaving.

00:12:43.370 --> 00:12:44.800
Then follow a couple
of steps behind.

00:12:48.540 --> 00:12:50.780
Listen to them go,
oh, I'm sorry.

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:51.890
I've forgotten your name.

00:12:51.890 --> 00:12:53.680
And then you come along and
say, well, goodbye,

00:12:53.680 --> 00:12:53.900
[INAUDIBLE].

00:12:53.900 --> 00:12:55.720
It was lovely to meet you.

00:12:55.720 --> 00:13:00.790
And everyone's amazed that you
have this immense memory

00:13:00.790 --> 00:13:03.650
because you've remembered 35
names which you learned in 10

00:13:03.650 --> 00:13:05.630
minutes three hours ago.

00:13:05.630 --> 00:13:07.720
But in fact, you're cheating.

00:13:07.720 --> 00:13:10.360
And of course, no one cheats
in public in Switzerland.

00:13:10.360 --> 00:13:11.690
So no one expects it.

00:13:11.690 --> 00:13:13.330
It works every time.

00:13:17.050 --> 00:13:21.914
S is for a word which doesn't
exist in any of

00:13:21.914 --> 00:13:25.740
the four Swiss languages.

00:13:25.740 --> 00:13:26.990
Spontaneity.

00:13:30.090 --> 00:13:32.220
I lived in London
for a long time.

00:13:32.220 --> 00:13:36.960
And in London, if you're in
someone's neighborhood, you do

00:13:36.960 --> 00:13:38.930
go and knock on the door and
say, literally, oh, I was in

00:13:38.930 --> 00:13:39.420
the neighborhood.

00:13:39.420 --> 00:13:40.660
I thought you were in.

00:13:40.660 --> 00:13:45.702
Because if they were to see you
walking down the street or

00:13:45.702 --> 00:13:48.264
saw your update on Facebook or
whatever, and say, Diccon

00:13:48.264 --> 00:13:49.650
didn't come and say hello.

00:13:49.650 --> 00:13:51.500
They would be really offended.

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:54.340
In Switzerland, it's exactly
the opposite.

00:13:54.340 --> 00:13:57.270
What I learned very quickly is
when I first arrived, I didn't

00:13:57.270 --> 00:13:57.920
have a job.

00:13:57.920 --> 00:14:00.830
I went to school in the mornings
to learn German from

00:14:00.830 --> 00:14:03.026
[INAUDIBLE] onwards.

00:14:03.026 --> 00:14:04.940
And in the afternoons, I
explored my new city.

00:14:04.940 --> 00:14:08.670
And I did know a couple of
Gregor's friends, and I knew

00:14:08.670 --> 00:14:09.470
where they lived.

00:14:09.470 --> 00:14:10.870
And I'd be walking past
and think, oh,

00:14:10.870 --> 00:14:11.450
so-and-so lives here.

00:14:11.450 --> 00:14:15.460
So I'd ring the bell, and there
would be this person

00:14:15.460 --> 00:14:19.269
with this look of utter
shock on their face.

00:14:19.269 --> 00:14:22.167
Did we have an appointment?

00:14:22.167 --> 00:14:26.390
And I thought, well, it's not
the doctor's surgery, but no,

00:14:26.390 --> 00:14:29.460
I was just spontaneously
passing by and thought,

00:14:29.460 --> 00:14:30.360
maybe you're in.

00:14:30.360 --> 00:14:32.160
It would be nice to chat.

00:14:32.160 --> 00:14:35.850
And so we'd stand on the
doorstep, making uncomfortable

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:39.080
small talk for 10 minutes or
so, and I would finally

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:43.240
realize that I was never
going to be invited in.

00:14:43.240 --> 00:14:46.320
And after this happened two or
three times, I realized that

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:50.930
spontaneous visits are
uncomfortable because the

00:14:50.930 --> 00:14:53.080
Swiss person is not prepared.

00:14:53.080 --> 00:14:53.850
They haven't cleaned the flat.

00:14:53.850 --> 00:14:54.870
They haven't bought
the Rivella.

00:14:54.870 --> 00:14:56.870
They haven't made the cookies.

00:14:56.870 --> 00:14:59.710
The haven't got everything
perfect.

00:14:59.710 --> 00:15:02.055
And a lot of Swiss people
are very house proud.

00:15:02.055 --> 00:15:06.156
And because the house is inside
the shell, whereas a

00:15:06.156 --> 00:15:09.140
lot of British and American
people use the house as a

00:15:09.140 --> 00:15:12.350
social extension, in
Switzerland, the house is part

00:15:12.350 --> 00:15:13.960
of inside the shell.

00:15:13.960 --> 00:15:17.810
So they're very proud of it and
always keen to show it in

00:15:17.810 --> 00:15:18.820
the best possible light.

00:15:18.820 --> 00:15:23.280
So if you turn up unannounced,
it may be always perfect,

00:15:23.280 --> 00:15:26.840
anyway, but it could not
be quite perfect.

00:15:26.840 --> 00:15:28.400
So you have to plan
a little bit.

00:15:28.400 --> 00:15:30.890
If I say to my Swiss friends now
I'm used to, well, let's

00:15:30.890 --> 00:15:32.670
go to the cinema sometime.

00:15:32.670 --> 00:15:34.240
And they'll get out
their handy--

00:15:34.240 --> 00:15:36.960
not their mobile phone but their
handy-- and say, well,

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:42.960
how about 17:35 on the
14th of April?

00:15:42.960 --> 00:15:46.470
And you go, OK, that's fine,
and get used to making

00:15:46.470 --> 00:15:49.290
appointments three
months ahead.

00:15:49.290 --> 00:15:53.320
But I have learned that you
can be spontaneous.

00:15:53.320 --> 00:15:56.345
You just have to plan
your spontaneity.

00:15:56.345 --> 00:15:59.180
It's a very Swiss concept.

00:15:59.180 --> 00:16:02.110
So I send a text or put a
message on Facebook or

00:16:02.110 --> 00:16:05.130
whatever and say, I'm
off next Friday.

00:16:05.130 --> 00:16:07.825
And if the weather's nice,
there's a high chance I'll go

00:16:07.825 --> 00:16:10.450
for a walk, and I may wander
through your neighborhood.

00:16:10.450 --> 00:16:12.880
And about 11 o'clock, it's
possible I might

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:13.870
ring on your doorbell.

00:16:13.870 --> 00:16:17.655
And if you happen to be home,
we could maybe sit down and

00:16:17.655 --> 00:16:19.930
have a chat for a few minutes,
if you're free.

00:16:19.930 --> 00:16:22.690
If not, no problem.

00:16:22.690 --> 00:16:26.440
And of course, they know that I
will turn up, and I turn up

00:16:26.440 --> 00:16:29.600
at about two minutes to 11:00,
just to feel a little bit

00:16:29.600 --> 00:16:31.320
spontaneous.

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:32.610
And everyone's happy.

00:16:32.610 --> 00:16:38.150
I ring on the doorbell
unannounced, roughly, and

00:16:38.150 --> 00:16:39.605
they're ready for me.

00:16:39.605 --> 00:16:43.610
Everything's tip top, another
phrase that went out of

00:16:43.610 --> 00:16:46.103
fashion in England about 1935.

00:16:46.103 --> 00:16:49.480
But here, people love
to say tip top.

00:16:49.480 --> 00:16:52.066
It feels like I'm talking to my
grandmother all the time.

00:16:56.510 --> 00:16:57.760
Swiss francs.

00:17:01.340 --> 00:17:03.630
Swiss people love money.

00:17:03.630 --> 00:17:04.839
And I'm not saying that
in a mean way.

00:17:04.839 --> 00:17:07.884
I'm saying actual, real money,
not pretend money like we have

00:17:07.884 --> 00:17:11.589
in America and Britain, plastic
and money that you

00:17:11.589 --> 00:17:12.710
never really see.

00:17:12.710 --> 00:17:14.740
Real money here.

00:17:14.740 --> 00:17:18.970
I worked for five years in a
bookshop, and it was a big

00:17:18.970 --> 00:17:21.170
surprise to me, having worked
five years in an English

00:17:21.170 --> 00:17:26.829
bookshop 100 years ago, where
most people pay with plastic.

00:17:26.829 --> 00:17:30.710
Here, over half of the customers
still pay with cash.

00:17:30.710 --> 00:17:33.800
And it's no surprise at
all if you're Swiss.

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:36.300
But if you're British, and it's
your first week at work,

00:17:36.300 --> 00:17:38.850
and you're on your own on the
shop floor, and the woman

00:17:38.850 --> 00:17:42.460
comes up and puts a book on the
counter, which costs 25

00:17:42.460 --> 00:17:43.485
francs or so.

00:17:43.485 --> 00:17:46.466
And she gives you a purple
piece of paper.

00:17:46.466 --> 00:17:50.330
And you look at it and think,
I've never seen a note with

00:17:50.330 --> 00:17:51.580
three zeroes on it.

00:17:54.366 --> 00:17:56.300
1,000 francs.

00:17:56.300 --> 00:17:59.310
It's like $1,000 just
on the counter.

00:17:59.310 --> 00:18:01.770
And so I look at it and look at
here, and she looks at me

00:18:01.770 --> 00:18:03.330
and looks at it.

00:18:03.330 --> 00:18:05.840
And she's obviously thinking,
why is this stupid man not

00:18:05.840 --> 00:18:08.650
just giving me my change,
like in any other shop?

00:18:08.650 --> 00:18:11.420
And I'm thinking, well, I didn't
even have 1,000 francs

00:18:11.420 --> 00:18:13.360
of change in my till.

00:18:13.360 --> 00:18:18.420
But also, shouldn't I hold it
up to the light or call the

00:18:18.420 --> 00:18:20.906
police or something?

00:18:20.906 --> 00:18:23.750
Because in Britain, our largest
note is a 50-pound

00:18:23.750 --> 00:18:27.498
note, which you never see,
really, unless you're a bank

00:18:27.498 --> 00:18:29.610
robber or a drug dealer.

00:18:29.610 --> 00:18:32.265
But normal people, you tend not
to get them very often.

00:18:32.265 --> 00:18:34.440
But here, 1,000-franc
notes are normal.

00:18:34.440 --> 00:18:36.630
People think they are normal.

00:18:36.630 --> 00:18:39.930
And it's a sure sign that you
are a tourist or a newly

00:18:39.930 --> 00:18:43.950
arrived foreigner if when you
go to co-op with a 200-franc

00:18:43.950 --> 00:18:47.099
note, you still apologize when
you hand it over, you say, I'm

00:18:47.099 --> 00:18:47.391
awfully sorry.

00:18:47.391 --> 00:18:49.690
It's all I've got.

00:18:49.690 --> 00:18:52.300
Because you're buying a bottle
of Coke for one franc 20, and

00:18:52.300 --> 00:18:54.770
the cashier looks at you, well,
why are you apologizing

00:18:54.770 --> 00:18:55.761
for giving me money?

00:18:55.761 --> 00:18:58.410
It's normal.

00:18:58.410 --> 00:19:00.110
My father has been visiting
Switzerland

00:19:00.110 --> 00:19:02.416
for eight years now.

00:19:02.416 --> 00:19:05.616
And he's still surprised when
the cash machine gives him a

00:19:05.616 --> 00:19:08.925
200-franc note, because in
England, you're lucky

00:19:08.925 --> 00:19:09.750
if you get a 20.

00:19:09.750 --> 00:19:12.720
It's normally 10s and 5s.

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:15.260
And what's interesting here
is the attitude to

00:19:15.260 --> 00:19:17.170
money is very different.

00:19:17.170 --> 00:19:23.815
It's all about trust, because
Swiss society runs on trust.

00:19:23.815 --> 00:19:26.807
Swiss people trust each other to
make the right decision, in

00:19:26.807 --> 00:19:29.970
a political sense, because
we have direct democracy.

00:19:29.970 --> 00:19:31.855
So it's a system of referenda.

00:19:31.855 --> 00:19:35.625
So the people always have a say,
or can always have a say,

00:19:35.625 --> 00:19:38.440
either at the beginning of a
process, like with the ban on

00:19:38.440 --> 00:19:39.670
new minarets.

00:19:39.670 --> 00:19:43.760
It was a referendum which now
has to be turned into law.

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:46.120
Or it's at the end of the
process that they have to

00:19:46.120 --> 00:19:49.840
ratify a treaty or say yes to
joining the United Nations,

00:19:49.840 --> 00:19:52.710
for instance, which didn't
happen for many, many years.

00:19:52.710 --> 00:19:54.940
So the Swiss people are
involved, but they trust each

00:19:54.940 --> 00:19:57.540
other to make the
right decision.

00:19:57.540 --> 00:19:59.230
And the same with many shops.

00:19:59.230 --> 00:20:01.000
I worked in a bookshop
in Bern.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:04.670
We had tables outside the shop
with books piled up on them,

00:20:04.670 --> 00:20:07.060
no member of staff there.

00:20:07.060 --> 00:20:10.730
And the shop trusts people to
just pick them up and bring

00:20:10.730 --> 00:20:11.782
them inside.

00:20:11.782 --> 00:20:14.430
Rather like my local co-up,
brings down the shutters at

00:20:14.430 --> 00:20:15.800
night and on a Sunday.

00:20:15.800 --> 00:20:18.620
And outside, there's still
compost and plants and

00:20:18.620 --> 00:20:19.520
everything.

00:20:19.520 --> 00:20:21.100
And they're still there
in the morning.

00:20:21.100 --> 00:20:22.160
So it's all about trust.

00:20:22.160 --> 00:20:26.085
And the cash society promotes
that trust, because if, like

00:20:26.085 --> 00:20:29.340
us, you order a new fridge,
you go to the

00:20:29.340 --> 00:20:30.440
shop, you order a fridge.

00:20:30.440 --> 00:20:32.310
You give them your
name and address.

00:20:32.310 --> 00:20:34.980
A few days later,
they deliver it.

00:20:34.980 --> 00:20:36.165
No one's taking a deposit.

00:20:36.165 --> 00:20:38.434
No one's taking a credit
card number.

00:20:38.434 --> 00:20:41.500
All they've done is deliver a
rather expensive fridge and

00:20:41.500 --> 00:20:43.262
say the bill will
be in the post.

00:20:43.262 --> 00:20:45.960
And the bill comes in the
post, and you have a

00:20:45.960 --> 00:20:47.020
month to pay it.

00:20:47.020 --> 00:20:49.750
And it's all very different
from when I worked in a

00:20:49.750 --> 00:20:53.310
British bookshop, where if we
took an order over the phone,

00:20:53.310 --> 00:20:54.610
it's like ordering on Amazon.

00:20:54.610 --> 00:20:57.120
You have to give your credit
card details before you even

00:20:57.120 --> 00:20:58.330
send the book out.

00:20:58.330 --> 00:21:01.900
So it's very much a
trustful society.

00:21:01.900 --> 00:21:05.320
And the cash is part of that,
because a lot of Swiss people,

00:21:05.320 --> 00:21:07.600
debt is a four-letter word.

00:21:07.600 --> 00:21:10.510
They don't have mortgages.

00:21:10.510 --> 00:21:14.680
And a lot of Swiss people do
not have a credit card.

00:21:14.680 --> 00:21:17.130
About a third have
a credit card.

00:21:17.130 --> 00:21:19.580
About a third don't have
a credit card.

00:21:19.580 --> 00:21:21.700
And about a third have a credit
card for going shopping

00:21:21.700 --> 00:21:24.200
in America.

00:21:24.200 --> 00:21:27.360
And really, it's because they
don't trust credit.

00:21:27.360 --> 00:21:29.880
They don't trust internet
shopping in the

00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:31.840
same way as we do.

00:21:31.840 --> 00:21:34.110
We've got a lot of customers
who would find a book on

00:21:34.110 --> 00:21:39.070
Amazon, print it out, and come
and order it in this shop,

00:21:39.070 --> 00:21:44.265
which for me was wonderful, as
a bookseller, but completely

00:21:44.265 --> 00:21:49.250
strange that they didn't trust
putting their personal details

00:21:49.250 --> 00:21:52.410
into a big website like
that or give them

00:21:52.410 --> 00:21:53.540
their credit card details.

00:21:53.540 --> 00:21:58.810
I pay my mobile phone bill
here by direct debit.

00:21:58.810 --> 00:22:01.020
A lot of my Swiss friends
think I'm crazy.

00:22:01.020 --> 00:22:04.400
Why on earth do you let a
company have your bank details

00:22:04.400 --> 00:22:06.440
and take money each month?

00:22:06.440 --> 00:22:08.740
It's because it's convenient.

00:22:08.740 --> 00:22:10.130
But it's all about trust.

00:22:10.130 --> 00:22:14.890
So it's a very interesting
reversal, or maybe a throwback

00:22:14.890 --> 00:22:16.600
to how it used to be.

00:22:16.600 --> 00:22:18.760
The other interesting thing
about the Swiss money is the

00:22:18.760 --> 00:22:23.665
coins haven't really changed
since about 1870s.

00:22:23.665 --> 00:22:27.310
In 1874, Helvetia, stood
up on the coin.

00:22:27.310 --> 00:22:28.210
She used to be sitting down.

00:22:28.210 --> 00:22:28.770
She stood up.

00:22:28.770 --> 00:22:31.580
That was a momentous change.

00:22:31.580 --> 00:22:37.090
And in 1978, an extra star was
added around the edge of the

00:22:37.090 --> 00:22:38.640
two-franc, one-franc, and
half-franc coins.

00:22:38.640 --> 00:22:41.835
Those are 23 stars
for the cantons.

00:22:41.835 --> 00:22:43.310
There used to be 22.

00:22:43.310 --> 00:22:46.000
And they had to squeeze an extra
one in when Jura became

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:48.760
a separate canton in 1978.

00:22:48.760 --> 00:22:51.710
But apart from that, they're
pretty much the

00:22:51.710 --> 00:22:52.780
same as they were.

00:22:52.780 --> 00:22:56.740
So it's quite usual for
sometimes in my change, I'll

00:22:56.740 --> 00:23:02.170
get a coin, which is 1930s,
1940s, and it's still doing

00:23:02.170 --> 00:23:03.050
the rounds.

00:23:03.050 --> 00:23:04.500
I don't really like
to touch it.

00:23:04.500 --> 00:23:05.360
I don't know where it's been.

00:23:05.360 --> 00:23:07.110
It's been in many, many
different hands.

00:23:07.110 --> 00:23:10.350
But I come from a country where
we change our coins

00:23:10.350 --> 00:23:10.860
practically every 10 years.

00:23:10.860 --> 00:23:11.460
They get smaller.

00:23:11.460 --> 00:23:12.010
They change shape.

00:23:12.010 --> 00:23:13.600
They introduce new ones.

00:23:13.600 --> 00:23:15.440
And here, it's very stable.

00:23:15.440 --> 00:23:17.185
It doesn't really change.

00:23:17.185 --> 00:23:21.445
Whereas the notes, there was a
major revolution in the notes

00:23:21.445 --> 00:23:23.390
about 10 years ago.

00:23:23.390 --> 00:23:28.425
They used to be taller as well
as longer, each note rather

00:23:28.425 --> 00:23:29.935
like the British notes.

00:23:29.935 --> 00:23:32.690
And then they decided, one,
you couldn't use automatic

00:23:32.690 --> 00:23:34.090
machines that easily.

00:23:34.090 --> 00:23:37.110
And two, the big notes, like
the 1,000-franc note, were

00:23:37.110 --> 00:23:38.940
just too big for people's
wallets.

00:23:38.940 --> 00:23:42.055
So they made them all the same
width, but each note 11

00:23:42.055 --> 00:23:44.740
millimeters longer than
the one before it.

00:23:44.740 --> 00:23:47.410
It's very precise.

00:23:47.410 --> 00:23:51.220
And then you get wonderful
things, like each note has a

00:23:51.220 --> 00:23:55.050
little symbol for blind people
to know what the note is.

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:57.320
So 10-franc note is a
little dot inside a

00:23:57.320 --> 00:23:58.945
circle that is raised.

00:23:58.945 --> 00:24:01.470
And this is the kind of thing
you never really notice until

00:24:01.470 --> 00:24:02.720
you research a book.

00:24:06.600 --> 00:24:08.095
N is for names.

00:24:08.095 --> 00:24:10.720
And that's not me.

00:24:10.720 --> 00:24:13.820
That is Basel Fasnacht, which
is coming up, one of the

00:24:13.820 --> 00:24:16.080
biggest festivals
in Switzerland.

00:24:16.080 --> 00:24:19.100
Really worth visiting, but
only if you like lots of

00:24:19.100 --> 00:24:22.120
music, lots of confetti,
and lots of people.

00:24:22.120 --> 00:24:24.605
If you don't like any of the
above, then don't go.

00:24:24.605 --> 00:24:27.060
Just watch it on television.

00:24:27.060 --> 00:24:31.220
Names here are also very
important, partly because you

00:24:31.220 --> 00:24:35.690
have to introduce yourself all
the time, even on the phone.

00:24:35.690 --> 00:24:38.100
If you phone a Swiss person,
particularly in the

00:24:38.100 --> 00:24:40.460
German-speaking part, not so
much in the French and

00:24:40.460 --> 00:24:40.980
Italian-speaking parts.

00:24:40.980 --> 00:24:43.455
But in the German-speaking part,
very often, they'll pick

00:24:43.455 --> 00:24:47.450
the phone and just say their
last name, which is very

00:24:47.450 --> 00:24:50.081
unfortunate if they have
a funny last name.

00:24:50.081 --> 00:24:52.800
I had a customer who
was Herr Wank.

00:24:52.800 --> 00:24:56.888
And every time I called him,
he would just go Wank?

00:24:56.888 --> 00:24:58.256
I was like, really?

00:24:58.256 --> 00:24:58.712
Here?

00:24:58.712 --> 00:25:00.540
Now?

00:25:00.540 --> 00:25:05.910
And it's too abrupt for me,
whereas in England, it's like,

00:25:05.910 --> 00:25:06.470
well, good morning.

00:25:06.470 --> 00:25:07.630
This is Diccon speaking.

00:25:07.630 --> 00:25:08.785
How can I help you,
if you're working

00:25:08.785 --> 00:25:09.940
in a shop, for instance.

00:25:09.940 --> 00:25:11.150
But names are very important.

00:25:11.150 --> 00:25:14.720
I once had a customer who I
had said, good morning.

00:25:14.720 --> 00:25:15.400
Diccon speaking.

00:25:15.400 --> 00:25:16.140
Can I help you?

00:25:16.140 --> 00:25:18.731
And she said, well, I need to
know your last name before you

00:25:18.731 --> 00:25:20.275
can help me.

00:25:20.275 --> 00:25:22.840
I said, OK, it's obviously
very important.

00:25:22.840 --> 00:25:28.150
The actual name itself
is partly controlled.

00:25:28.150 --> 00:25:30.180
It's not very strictly
controlled.

00:25:30.180 --> 00:25:33.510
There isn't a list of first
names that you have to give,

00:25:33.510 --> 00:25:35.460
have to choose from.

00:25:35.460 --> 00:25:37.930
But the first name you give your
baby has to be approved

00:25:37.930 --> 00:25:40.790
by the community registrar.

00:25:40.790 --> 00:25:43.630
You have to give the baby a
name within three days.

00:25:43.630 --> 00:25:46.920
You can't take the baby home
and think, well, she looks

00:25:46.920 --> 00:25:47.355
like a Michelle.

00:25:47.355 --> 00:25:49.410
We'll call her Michelle
after a week or so.

00:25:49.410 --> 00:25:51.200
The name has to be given before

00:25:51.200 --> 00:25:53.390
the baby leaves hospital.

00:25:53.390 --> 00:25:56.680
And there are certain rules.

00:25:56.680 --> 00:26:01.330
So you can't use bad-boy names,
like Judas and Cain.

00:26:01.330 --> 00:26:05.230
You can't use family names
as first name,

00:26:05.230 --> 00:26:07.475
so no Harrison Ford.

00:26:07.475 --> 00:26:09.440
You can't use place names.

00:26:09.440 --> 00:26:10.850
No Paris Hilton.

00:26:10.850 --> 00:26:12.100
Hurrah.

00:26:14.140 --> 00:26:17.180
You can't make up names just
because they sound nice.

00:26:17.180 --> 00:26:20.270
Or you can't give a
baby a name which

00:26:20.270 --> 00:26:22.420
would open it to ridicule.

00:26:22.420 --> 00:26:25.140
So for instance, if your surname
is Head, you can't

00:26:25.140 --> 00:26:27.300
call your son Richard
if it were in an

00:26:27.300 --> 00:26:30.270
English-speaking country.

00:26:30.270 --> 00:26:34.800
You can't call your son Adolf
Hitler like a couple in

00:26:34.800 --> 00:26:36.960
America did a few years ago.

00:26:36.960 --> 00:26:40.000
So anything that will harm the
child emotionally, physically,

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:41.930
mentally, is not allowed.

00:26:41.930 --> 00:26:44.820
And it has to be approved
by the registrar.

00:26:44.820 --> 00:26:47.820
It sounds very controlling, but
it's actually for the well

00:26:47.820 --> 00:26:51.210
being of the child so that you
don't get children like the

00:26:51.210 --> 00:26:55.115
little girl in New Zealand who
was called Talula-Does-The-

00:26:55.115 --> 00:26:58.885
Hula-From-Hawaii,
all hyphenated.

00:26:58.885 --> 00:27:01.110
That was her given name.

00:27:01.110 --> 00:27:03.880
That would never be allowed
here, and probably

00:27:03.880 --> 00:27:05.210
rightly so, I think.

00:27:05.210 --> 00:27:06.925
Which is why you get a lot of
women called Doris Muller.

00:27:11.950 --> 00:27:16.560
E is for Emmentaler, possibly
the most famous Swiss product,

00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:19.570
Swiss cheese, as it's generally
called in some parts

00:27:19.570 --> 00:27:21.160
of the world.

00:27:21.160 --> 00:27:23.080
And the interesting thing about
Emmentaler, it's one of

00:27:23.080 --> 00:27:26.940
those Swiss products that
everyone knows is Swiss.

00:27:26.940 --> 00:27:29.190
And typically, Swiss
firms, like Swiss

00:27:29.190 --> 00:27:30.850
people, are very modest.

00:27:30.850 --> 00:27:35.230
They're not wonderful at
shouting to the world, we've

00:27:35.230 --> 00:27:35.830
invented this thing.

00:27:35.830 --> 00:27:36.520
It's wonderful.

00:27:36.520 --> 00:27:37.510
It's great.

00:27:37.510 --> 00:27:39.424
This is the best thing
in the world.

00:27:39.424 --> 00:27:41.794
They say, oh yeah, by the way,
we've invented something

00:27:41.794 --> 00:27:43.545
rather interesting, and
maybe you'd like it.

00:27:43.545 --> 00:27:44.520
Or not even that.

00:27:44.520 --> 00:27:47.930
They just put it out there and
hope it sells itself somehow.

00:27:47.930 --> 00:27:52.135
So there are lots of Swiss
inventions which are famous

00:27:52.135 --> 00:27:54.740
but not famous for
being Swiss.

00:27:54.740 --> 00:27:58.778
So Velcro, for instance, the
Toilet Duck, electric

00:27:58.778 --> 00:28:04.990
toothbrush, LSD, absinthe,
really useful everyday things.

00:28:04.990 --> 00:28:07.752
Cellophane, tin foil.

00:28:07.752 --> 00:28:10.870
These are all Swiss inventions,
but pretty much,

00:28:10.870 --> 00:28:13.572
even Swiss people probably
don't know they're Swiss,

00:28:13.572 --> 00:28:15.655
because they've just been
invented, and they think, oh,

00:28:15.655 --> 00:28:16.350
that's great.

00:28:16.350 --> 00:28:17.740
And out they go.

00:28:17.740 --> 00:28:21.390
And so it's very interesting
to see Swiss firms now

00:28:21.390 --> 00:28:25.530
changing slowly to deal with
social media, to deal with

00:28:25.530 --> 00:28:29.380
different forms of selling,
because it's not really in

00:28:29.380 --> 00:28:35.650
their genes to be very forward
and to be very proactive.

00:28:35.650 --> 00:28:41.080
So sometimes, it can be hard
for them to enter into the

00:28:41.080 --> 00:28:43.310
big, wide world outside
their coconut.

00:28:43.310 --> 00:28:45.070
So Switzerland, in a way,
is like a coconut.

00:28:45.070 --> 00:28:48.312
The mountains are the shell,
and it's very nice and

00:28:48.312 --> 00:28:49.720
comfortable in the
internal market.

00:28:49.720 --> 00:28:52.941
But selling to the outside
world can be scary.

00:28:52.941 --> 00:28:56.900
And as for the Emmentaler
itself, well, the holes are

00:28:56.900 --> 00:28:59.920
officially called eyes.

00:28:59.920 --> 00:29:04.180
And they are, officially,
the CO2 released during

00:29:04.180 --> 00:29:07.470
fermentation by the bacteria
that are added So in other

00:29:07.470 --> 00:29:09.150
words, they're bacteria
farts that are

00:29:09.150 --> 00:29:12.170
trapped inside the cheese.

00:29:12.170 --> 00:29:15.720
But it has to be said,
Emmentaler, my favorite part

00:29:15.720 --> 00:29:18.125
of the cheese is the hole.

00:29:18.125 --> 00:29:19.375
I tend to leave the rest.

00:29:23.570 --> 00:29:24.340
Penultimate S--

00:29:24.340 --> 00:29:26.210
unfortunately, "Swissness"
has lots of Ses.

00:29:26.210 --> 00:29:30.435
I had to work really
hard with the Ses.

00:29:30.435 --> 00:29:32.670
It's for Sundays.

00:29:32.670 --> 00:29:35.220
Sundays were abolished in
America and Britain

00:29:35.220 --> 00:29:36.870
about 20 years ago.

00:29:36.870 --> 00:29:38.620
Basically, Sunday is
like any other day.

00:29:38.620 --> 00:29:38.995
You can go shopping.

00:29:38.995 --> 00:29:42.240
You can do pretty much whatever
you want, whereas

00:29:42.240 --> 00:29:46.830
here, Sundays are still
something special.

00:29:46.830 --> 00:29:51.542
Not necessarily a day of
religion, because although

00:29:51.542 --> 00:29:53.410
it's a little bit more religious
here than in other

00:29:53.410 --> 00:29:54.730
countries, it's not
that religious.

00:29:54.730 --> 00:29:56.470
Some cantons are Catholic.

00:29:56.470 --> 00:29:58.370
Some cantons are Protestant.

00:29:58.370 --> 00:30:01.040
You only really notice when
the Catholic cantons have

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:02.780
holiday which the Protestant
cantons don't.

00:30:02.780 --> 00:30:04.660
And you think, oh, I'll
go to Lucerne today.

00:30:04.660 --> 00:30:06.750
And you get there, and
everything's shut because

00:30:06.750 --> 00:30:09.872
they're celebrating Mary going
to heaven or Mary having a

00:30:09.872 --> 00:30:13.700
little lamb or Mary
doing something.

00:30:13.700 --> 00:30:16.442
And the Protestant cantons, of
course, are hardworking.

00:30:16.442 --> 00:30:18.330
They have far fewer holidays.

00:30:18.330 --> 00:30:20.600
The best place to live,
by the way, is Ticino.

00:30:20.600 --> 00:30:24.620
That's 15 public holidays, as
opposed to eight in Bern,

00:30:24.620 --> 00:30:25.790
because they celebrate whatever

00:30:25.790 --> 00:30:26.760
their saints are doing.

00:30:26.760 --> 00:30:30.370
It's an excuse for a day off.

00:30:30.370 --> 00:30:32.660
So Sundays is not down
to religion.

00:30:32.660 --> 00:30:34.720
It's about having
a day of rest.

00:30:34.720 --> 00:30:37.285
That's why the shops aren't
open, except in the stations

00:30:37.285 --> 00:30:39.190
or the airport.

00:30:39.190 --> 00:30:43.965
That's why you can't
do your recycling.

00:30:43.965 --> 00:30:46.940
It may be God's holy day, but
you can't save the planet,

00:30:46.940 --> 00:30:49.510
because if you do what I did
and put some bottles in the

00:30:49.510 --> 00:30:53.180
bottle bank on a Sunday, you get
told off very quickly for

00:30:53.180 --> 00:30:55.170
creating too much noise.

00:30:55.170 --> 00:30:58.290
You also very often can't do
things like clean your car,

00:30:58.290 --> 00:31:01.460
mow the grass, wash the windows,
do any DIY, because

00:31:01.460 --> 00:31:04.541
that's all disturbing someone
else's peace.

00:31:04.541 --> 00:31:08.910
And in buildings where you
have communal laundries,

00:31:08.910 --> 00:31:12.678
sometimes the laundry room is
actually locked on Sunday.

00:31:12.678 --> 00:31:14.820
So you can't even
do your washing.

00:31:14.820 --> 00:31:16.670
And it's not about controlling
your life.

00:31:16.670 --> 00:31:18.390
It's about making sure
that everyone

00:31:18.390 --> 00:31:20.730
has a good life balance.

00:31:20.730 --> 00:31:23.350
So what do Swiss people
do on Sunday?

00:31:23.350 --> 00:31:28.492
Well, typically, there's
the cinema.

00:31:28.492 --> 00:31:30.770
Visit friends, as long as you've
told them in advance

00:31:30.770 --> 00:31:32.020
that you're coming.

00:31:35.160 --> 00:31:37.630
Go to a museum, because they're
usually shut on

00:31:37.630 --> 00:31:40.180
Mondays, because they can't
cope with opening

00:31:40.180 --> 00:31:41.070
every day of the week.

00:31:41.070 --> 00:31:42.380
That's too much.

00:31:42.380 --> 00:31:45.430
Or you go for a walk through a
lovely place like this, the

00:31:45.430 --> 00:31:47.720
Eiger Nordwand, north
face of the Eiger.

00:31:47.720 --> 00:31:49.550
It's one of my favorite walks.

00:31:49.550 --> 00:31:53.439
But a Swiss walk is not
a British walk.

00:31:56.277 --> 00:31:58.800
A British walk is a stroll
through a meadow for an hour

00:31:58.800 --> 00:32:03.310
or so, finishing at
a pub with a pint.

00:32:03.310 --> 00:32:07.850
A Swiss walk is at least five
hours long, has height

00:32:07.850 --> 00:32:13.490
differences of 500 meters,
definitely no pub at the end,

00:32:13.490 --> 00:32:16.370
and you're a panting wreck
behind all your Swiss friends,

00:32:16.370 --> 00:32:19.725
who have marched off with their
sticks and their boots.

00:32:19.725 --> 00:32:20.410
I went on one walk.

00:32:20.410 --> 00:32:23.405
Never again.

00:32:23.405 --> 00:32:25.290
I now meet my friends
at the top.

00:32:25.290 --> 00:32:26.905
I take the cable car and
say, well, I'll meet

00:32:26.905 --> 00:32:27.650
you there for lunch.

00:32:27.650 --> 00:32:28.420
That's fine.

00:32:28.420 --> 00:32:30.560
And I bring the picnic.

00:32:30.560 --> 00:32:32.950
And they do the exercise.

00:32:32.950 --> 00:32:35.356
And I just get up three hours
late, because they all get up

00:32:35.356 --> 00:32:37.440
at 6 o'clock in the morning
on a Sunday.

00:32:37.440 --> 00:32:39.560
And the train is packed, because
it's a beautiful day.

00:32:39.560 --> 00:32:40.960
And it's like rush hour.

00:32:40.960 --> 00:32:42.759
And you have to run
to get a seat.

00:32:42.759 --> 00:32:45.980
And I say, I'll get up at 9:00
and catch a later train and

00:32:45.980 --> 00:32:47.345
meet them at the top.

00:32:47.345 --> 00:32:49.810
That's what Sundays
are about here.

00:32:49.810 --> 00:32:53.790
And it actually takes a bit of
getting used to, after living

00:32:53.790 --> 00:32:56.010
in London where everything
is 24 hours.

00:32:56.010 --> 00:32:59.510
At the beginning, I was
thinking, oh my lord, it's 4

00:32:59.510 --> 00:33:00.410
o'clock on a Saturday.

00:33:00.410 --> 00:33:02.520
Nothing's going to be open until
9 o'clock on Monday.

00:33:02.520 --> 00:33:04.620
And you have to rush to the
supermarket, because

00:33:04.620 --> 00:33:07.270
otherwise, you're not going
to have anything to eat.

00:33:07.270 --> 00:33:10.780
Or you have to face the scrum
that is the Migros in the

00:33:10.780 --> 00:33:14.730
station, where very often, it's
one in, one out, because

00:33:14.730 --> 00:33:16.650
it's so busy inside.

00:33:16.650 --> 00:33:18.776
But you get used to it,
and you actually

00:33:18.776 --> 00:33:21.560
appreciate your Sundays.

00:33:21.560 --> 00:33:26.760
The difficult thing when you
first arrive is that Sundays

00:33:26.760 --> 00:33:28.140
aren't just Sundays.

00:33:28.140 --> 00:33:30.300
Holidays are Sundays as well.

00:33:30.300 --> 00:33:34.020
So on holidays, everything
is shut.

00:33:34.020 --> 00:33:39.600
So logically, the day before a
holiday is a Saturday, even

00:33:39.600 --> 00:33:44.040
when it isn't, because a
holiday is a Sunday.

00:33:44.040 --> 00:33:47.460
So on the day before Good
Friday, for instance, Maundy

00:33:47.460 --> 00:33:49.935
Thursday, everything
shuts at 5 o'clock

00:33:49.935 --> 00:33:52.362
because it is a Saturday.

00:33:52.362 --> 00:33:54.720
Now, that you can just about get
your head around, because

00:33:54.720 --> 00:33:56.350
Good Friday is the same
all the time.

00:33:56.350 --> 00:34:00.570
When it gets difficult is the
holidays that move around and

00:34:00.570 --> 00:34:01.910
take you by surprise.

00:34:01.910 --> 00:34:04.552
So like the 1st of August, and
then suddenly, you have to

00:34:04.552 --> 00:34:06.480
remember, oh, it's
the 31st of July.

00:34:06.480 --> 00:34:08.679
Not that it's Wednesday, but
it's the 31st of July, so it's

00:34:08.679 --> 00:34:10.940
a Saturday.

00:34:10.940 --> 00:34:14.639
Or again, going to Lucerne or
another Catholic canton when

00:34:14.639 --> 00:34:18.835
they're celebrating something
that Mary did, allegedly, then

00:34:18.835 --> 00:34:22.370
you have to remember that the
day before the day that Mary

00:34:22.370 --> 00:34:27.804
did something, everyone has to
get ready and rest and close

00:34:27.804 --> 00:34:31.389
early to celebrate Mary's
doing things.

00:34:31.389 --> 00:34:35.110
So you have to remember that all
these religious holidays,

00:34:35.110 --> 00:34:37.520
which in England, we got rid
of and made into very

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:41.035
anonymous spring bank holiday,
here are still called

00:34:41.035 --> 00:34:44.085
Ascension Day and Pentecost.

00:34:44.085 --> 00:34:45.695
I didn't even know what
happened on Pentecost

00:34:45.695 --> 00:34:46.665
until I came here.

00:34:46.665 --> 00:34:48.690
And I learned very quickly,
something to do

00:34:48.690 --> 00:34:50.060
with the Holy Spirit.

00:34:50.060 --> 00:34:53.630
In my children's book, it had
the apostles with little gas

00:34:53.630 --> 00:34:55.704
flames above their heads.

00:34:55.704 --> 00:34:57.930
That's how I learned
what Pentecost was.

00:34:57.930 --> 00:35:00.230
But of course, remember, the
day before Pentecost is

00:35:00.230 --> 00:35:01.426
therefore a Saturday.

00:35:01.426 --> 00:35:05.210
So you just have to be
a bit more prepared.

00:35:05.210 --> 00:35:09.270
The last S is for Swinglish.

00:35:09.270 --> 00:35:10.950
And Swinglish is the English
that a lot of

00:35:10.950 --> 00:35:12.982
Swiss people speak.

00:35:12.982 --> 00:35:15.672
A lot of Swiss people speak
wonderful English.

00:35:15.672 --> 00:35:17.540
[GERMAN].

00:35:17.540 --> 00:35:22.140
And a lot of Swiss people
speak their version of

00:35:22.140 --> 00:35:25.710
wonderful English, which
isn't always the same.

00:35:25.710 --> 00:35:29.500
And the problem is, as the
English speaker, you are

00:35:29.500 --> 00:35:32.690
expected to understand their
English, because they think

00:35:32.690 --> 00:35:34.780
it's English.

00:35:34.780 --> 00:35:38.540
So for instance, in this
picture, if you were to park

00:35:38.540 --> 00:35:42.960
your car in a space marked
"car," as a friend of mine

00:35:42.960 --> 00:35:50.150
did, she did notice it
was a very big space.

00:35:50.150 --> 00:35:52.630
So she parked at right angles,
thinking that everyone had to

00:35:52.630 --> 00:35:56.742
do the same so that we could fit
lots of cars in the space.

00:35:56.742 --> 00:35:57.940
It's logical.

00:35:57.940 --> 00:35:59.330
Space marked "car."
I have a car.

00:35:59.330 --> 00:36:01.430
I park my car.

00:36:01.430 --> 00:36:04.200
Two hours later, I come back to
my parked car in the "car"

00:36:04.200 --> 00:36:07.200
space, and I have a ticket,
because, of course, "car"

00:36:07.200 --> 00:36:09.130
doesn't mean car.

00:36:09.130 --> 00:36:12.860
"Car" means coach or bus,
typically a tour bus.

00:36:12.860 --> 00:36:15.990
That's why the space
is so big.

00:36:15.990 --> 00:36:19.117
But to English speakers, it's
blindingly obvious that it's a

00:36:19.117 --> 00:36:20.990
space for cars.

00:36:20.990 --> 00:36:24.000
So you're very surprised
to get a ticket.

