number, and they will look
at you, what's a

00:36:32.280 --> 00:36:35.250
number that's handy?

00:36:35.250 --> 00:36:38.190
One of those I wrote on my hand
in a club last night?

00:36:38.190 --> 00:36:39.730
I'm not really sure.

00:36:39.730 --> 00:36:42.300
Because you forget that some
English words-- because

00:36:42.300 --> 00:36:45.940
"handy" is an English word
meaning "convenient." But you

00:36:45.940 --> 00:36:47.290
forget that they have different
meanings here.

00:36:47.290 --> 00:36:49.605
You get so used to the Swinglish
meaning that you use

00:36:49.605 --> 00:36:51.975
it when you go back to England,
and everyone think

00:36:51.975 --> 00:36:55.020
you're a little bit strange.

00:36:55.020 --> 00:36:59.890
Far more embarrassing is, for
instance, if you're talking

00:36:59.890 --> 00:37:02.440
about your hobbies-- you're
making small talk--

00:37:02.440 --> 00:37:05.620
and you're an English
speaker--

00:37:05.620 --> 00:37:07.720
sorry, if you're a Swiss person
speaking English, as a

00:37:07.720 --> 00:37:09.320
friend of mine did.

00:37:09.320 --> 00:37:15.182
And she said her hobby was
riding old timers, which, of

00:37:15.182 --> 00:37:17.330
course, for her meant she loved
riding around in vintage

00:37:17.330 --> 00:37:20.710
cars and vintage car rallies,
because an old timer is a

00:37:20.710 --> 00:37:22.330
vintage car.

00:37:22.330 --> 00:37:25.655
But the English person she was
speaking to, who was an old

00:37:25.655 --> 00:37:30.920
man, thought that she liked
having sex with old men, and

00:37:30.920 --> 00:37:32.290
she was being very,
very forward.

00:37:35.110 --> 00:37:36.620
But for her, the meaning
was clear.

00:37:36.620 --> 00:37:38.419
And for him, the meaning
was clear.

00:37:41.257 --> 00:37:43.190
It was only when I explained
the two different meanings

00:37:43.190 --> 00:37:45.106
that they both went very red.

00:37:47.980 --> 00:37:51.980
And then you get invited to very
formal functions, dress

00:37:51.980 --> 00:37:54.379
code smoking.

00:37:54.379 --> 00:37:58.163
And I'm thinking,
I don't smoke.

00:37:58.163 --> 00:37:59.582
And I go--

00:37:59.582 --> 00:38:03.020
or even if I did smoke, how
can I wear a smoking?

00:38:03.020 --> 00:38:04.650
How can I wear a verb?

00:38:04.650 --> 00:38:06.850
Sounds like some weird,
fancy dress party.

00:38:06.850 --> 00:38:09.723
Come as your favorite
verb participle.

00:38:09.723 --> 00:38:13.180
But of course, a smoking is a
dinner jacket or a tuxedo.

00:38:13.180 --> 00:38:16.320
So it can be very confusing
when same words

00:38:16.320 --> 00:38:18.060
have different meanings.

00:38:18.060 --> 00:38:19.473
There are lots of English
words which

00:38:19.473 --> 00:38:20.170
have the same meaning--

00:38:20.170 --> 00:38:23.235
snap, online, quickie, Google.

00:38:26.630 --> 00:38:29.590
But there are lots of words
which have different meanings.

00:38:29.590 --> 00:38:32.480
And sometimes, it can be
very embarrassing.

00:38:32.480 --> 00:38:36.480
I remember a customer in the
shop came in and spoke in

00:38:36.480 --> 00:38:41.350
English, so I presumed we were
speaking English together.

00:38:41.350 --> 00:38:44.980
And she said, do you have that
book about a shag in the woods

00:38:44.980 --> 00:38:46.230
with Jesus?

00:38:49.330 --> 00:38:50.800
I was very professional.

00:38:50.800 --> 00:38:52.270
I kept a straight face.

00:38:55.220 --> 00:38:58.060
And I thought, well, it's the
wrong bookshop for that.

00:39:00.610 --> 00:39:04.480
And then I realized that for a
Swiss German, the "G" at the

00:39:04.480 --> 00:39:07.176
end is the same as
a "K" at the end.

00:39:07.176 --> 00:39:09.666
So it was the shack,
not the shag.

00:39:09.666 --> 00:39:11.820
And of course, there is a very
famous book called "The Shack"

00:39:11.820 --> 00:39:13.515
about a man who spends
a weekend in

00:39:13.515 --> 00:39:14.140
the woods with Jesus.

00:39:14.140 --> 00:39:17.550
I don't know what they
were doing there.

00:39:17.550 --> 00:39:20.235
But then to I went and got
the book, "The Shack,"

00:39:20.235 --> 00:39:21.900
and gave it to her.

00:39:21.900 --> 00:39:25.851
And it's very hard, sometimes,
for the Swiss ear to hear the

00:39:25.851 --> 00:39:29.562
difference at the end between
a "guh" and a "kuh," whereas

00:39:29.562 --> 00:39:33.020
for an English ear,
it's much clearer.

00:39:33.020 --> 00:39:37.280
And then, of course, there are
situations where you end up

00:39:37.280 --> 00:39:38.870
looking really, really
stupid--

00:39:38.870 --> 00:39:41.260
or I do, anyway--

00:39:41.260 --> 00:39:44.510
which is why I think this is one
of many people's favorite

00:39:44.510 --> 00:39:48.500
part of the book, because I do
look particularly stupid.

00:39:48.500 --> 00:39:49.750
But I'll read it anyway.

00:39:52.314 --> 00:39:55.440
Lots of Ses, so I
need some water.

00:39:55.440 --> 00:39:58.030
And this, I haven't been
in the bookshop long.

00:39:58.030 --> 00:40:00.500
I didn't realize that people
didn't speak my English at

00:40:00.500 --> 00:40:02.420
that point.

00:40:02.420 --> 00:40:03.930
"Swiss customer--

00:40:03.930 --> 00:40:06.810
'I need a book on cheeses.'
'OK, I'll show you what we

00:40:06.810 --> 00:40:07.960
have in the cookery section.

00:40:07.960 --> 00:40:10.624
I'll get out our three books on
cheese.' Customer shaking

00:40:10.624 --> 00:40:13.680
her head, 'Not cheese,
cheeses.'

00:40:13.680 --> 00:40:19.350
At this point, I'm wondering,
does cheese have a plural?

00:40:19.350 --> 00:40:23.310
Was it like sheep, with none, or
more like fish, plural when

00:40:23.310 --> 00:40:25.140
there's more than one type?

00:40:25.140 --> 00:40:27.060
Or was this a Swinglish
plural, like

00:40:27.060 --> 00:40:30.190
informations and behaviors?

00:40:30.190 --> 00:40:32.850
Not wanting to get into a
discussion on that, I try

00:40:32.850 --> 00:40:36.140
again, going with her plural
in the hope that it helps.

00:40:36.140 --> 00:40:40.730
'So, you're looking for
something on cheeses.' ' Yes,'

00:40:40.730 --> 00:40:47.960
the customer says, 'books on
holy cheeses.' 'Oh, you want a

00:40:47.960 --> 00:40:51.785
book on Swiss cheeses.'
Customer, looking me as if I'm

00:40:51.785 --> 00:40:59.790
simple, 'there is no Swiss
cheeses.' I'm now thinking

00:40:59.790 --> 00:41:02.892
about her singular verb
with her plural noun.

00:41:02.892 --> 00:41:06.986
'We do have something on Swiss
cheeses.' Customer now very

00:41:06.986 --> 00:41:11.510
irritated, 'cheeses
was not Swiss.

00:41:11.510 --> 00:41:17.520
Cheeses was the son of God.'
'Oh, you mean Jesus.' 'This is

00:41:17.520 --> 00:41:18.100
what I'm saying.

00:41:18.100 --> 00:41:21.290
Books on cheeses.'"

00:41:21.290 --> 00:41:22.970
And of course, for me,
it was very clear.

00:41:22.970 --> 00:41:25.400
And for her, it was
very clear.

00:41:25.400 --> 00:41:27.820
And we just weren't talking
about the same thing.

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:29.690
And for all the other customers
and my Swiss

00:41:29.690 --> 00:41:33.038
colleagues, who were helpless on
the floor laughing, no one

00:41:33.038 --> 00:41:35.870
coming to my aid, it
was also very clear

00:41:35.870 --> 00:41:39.434
that I was very stupid.

00:41:39.434 --> 00:41:42.150
And Swiss friends of mine who
have heard me tell that story

00:41:42.150 --> 00:41:45.203
many, many times now say,
I still can't hear the

00:41:45.203 --> 00:41:47.500
difference.

00:41:47.500 --> 00:41:51.150
Because, of course, a J for
Swiss German speakers is a

00:41:51.150 --> 00:41:57.230
"yuh," and a CH is a "huh." So
they're very distinct, where

00:41:57.230 --> 00:42:01.250
to a Swiss ear, a juh and a chuh
sound exactly the same.

00:42:01.250 --> 00:42:04.740
So if you happen to be a man
called Jerry from Vancouver,

00:42:04.740 --> 00:42:07.020
you have to be very careful
what you say when you

00:42:07.020 --> 00:42:08.080
introduce yourself.

00:42:08.080 --> 00:42:11.187
"Hi, I'm Cherry from Wankouver"
is what you tend to

00:42:11.187 --> 00:42:15.530
get, because Jerry and Cherry
are exactly the same name.

00:42:15.530 --> 00:42:18.270
My boyfriend goes chogging.

00:42:18.270 --> 00:42:20.130
The first time, he said, I'm
just going chogging with

00:42:20.130 --> 00:42:21.535
friends, I thought, should
I be jealous?

00:42:21.535 --> 00:42:24.640
What is he doing?

00:42:24.640 --> 00:42:27.660
Something in parked cars that is
vaguely illegal, I'm sure.

00:42:30.360 --> 00:42:31.810
So that's Swinglish.

00:42:31.810 --> 00:42:34.152
It's the last part
of Swissness.

00:42:34.152 --> 00:42:37.115
And that's really the funny
side of what it's

00:42:37.115 --> 00:42:37.585
like to live here.

00:42:37.585 --> 00:42:39.615
Obviously, there's a serious
side-- the political system,

00:42:39.615 --> 00:42:42.910
the geography, the history, the
wars, the people, all of

00:42:42.910 --> 00:42:45.550
which I go into in the
book in some detail.

00:42:45.550 --> 00:42:47.550
So I learned a lot very quickly,
because, of course,

00:42:47.550 --> 00:42:51.180
in Britain, we learn nothing
about Switzerland, apart from

00:42:51.180 --> 00:42:53.463
banks and "Heidi."
That's about it.

00:42:53.463 --> 00:42:55.954
We certainly don't learn about
Swiss history and the original

00:42:55.954 --> 00:42:58.710
cantons or about the direct
democracy system, partly

00:42:58.710 --> 00:43:00.930
because we don't even understand
our own system, and

00:43:00.930 --> 00:43:03.400
partly because we'd probably
be jealous if we actually

00:43:03.400 --> 00:43:05.520
thought, wow, they get asked
every three months what they

00:43:05.520 --> 00:43:07.540
think, not every four years.

00:43:07.540 --> 00:43:08.460
Seems amazing.

00:43:08.460 --> 00:43:10.360
And the country actually
functions.

00:43:10.360 --> 00:43:14.040
How can a country function if
the people keep having to make

00:43:14.040 --> 00:43:14.730
the decisions?

00:43:14.730 --> 00:43:19.220
It's just not democracy
at all, really, is it?

00:43:19.220 --> 00:43:22.270
So there is a serious
side to living here.

00:43:22.270 --> 00:43:27.190
But I focus on some of the
serious parts and some of the

00:43:27.190 --> 00:43:28.620
more amusing parts.

00:43:28.620 --> 00:43:32.710
The book came out originally
in 2010.

00:43:32.710 --> 00:43:34.930
Very happily for me, it became
the bestselling English book

00:43:34.930 --> 00:43:36.370
in Switzerland.

00:43:36.370 --> 00:43:39.265
And as Dana said,
the "Financial

00:43:39.265 --> 00:43:40.710
Times" Book of the Year.

00:43:40.710 --> 00:43:43.160
It's also in German.

00:43:43.160 --> 00:43:46.090
So my mother-in-law is very
happy, because she speaks two

00:43:46.090 --> 00:43:51.270
words of English, "happy
Christmas." She has progressed

00:43:51.270 --> 00:43:53.200
to "happy birthday" now.

00:43:53.200 --> 00:43:54.710
So she was very happy
to finally

00:43:54.710 --> 00:43:55.980
read the book in German.

00:43:55.980 --> 00:43:57.265
It has a different title.

00:43:57.265 --> 00:43:59.580
I have progressed from
being a watcher to an

00:43:59.580 --> 00:44:02.700
understander, [GERMAN].

00:44:02.700 --> 00:44:07.270
It also, very interestingly,
has a toilet on the cover.

00:44:07.270 --> 00:44:09.500
This is a very famous Swiss
toilet up in the mountains,

00:44:09.500 --> 00:44:11.160
one which you have to walk
to get to, obviously.

00:44:13.686 --> 00:44:16.820
And I've even had people send
me pictures-- not of them on

00:44:16.820 --> 00:44:20.870
the toilet but of the toilet,
sending me GPS coordinates to

00:44:20.870 --> 00:44:22.940
show me where it is
in Graubunden.

00:44:22.940 --> 00:44:25.910
It is, apparently, a famous
toilet, but it's a toilet

00:44:25.910 --> 00:44:27.540
nonetheless.

00:44:27.540 --> 00:44:30.940
And then the French edition
comes in June this year,

00:44:30.940 --> 00:44:33.700
again, with a different title,
different cover, just to

00:44:33.700 --> 00:44:36.960
confuse everyone, especially
the booksellers.

00:44:36.960 --> 00:44:40.730
And last year, a little book
of facts came out called

00:44:40.730 --> 00:44:42.270
"Swisscellany," or

00:44:42.270 --> 00:44:44.860
Swiss-cell-any, if you're American.

00:44:44.860 --> 00:44:47.372
And it's one of those books of
facts that you dip in and out

00:44:47.372 --> 00:44:49.870
of and think, well, I never
needed to know that, but it's

00:44:49.870 --> 00:44:51.170
quite interesting.

00:44:51.170 --> 00:44:54.170
So the Swiss people on the
"Titanic" and which ones died,

00:44:54.170 --> 00:44:55.520
which ones survived.

00:44:55.520 --> 00:44:58.635
Which cantons have
the most cows?

00:44:58.635 --> 00:45:00.230
It's Canton Bern, by the way.

00:45:00.230 --> 00:45:02.560
All the Emmentaler cheese.

00:45:02.560 --> 00:45:05.150
Or all the characters in
"Heidi," or Swiss winners at

00:45:05.150 --> 00:45:08.370
the Oscars and the Olympics,
things like that.

00:45:08.370 --> 00:45:10.500
Kind of useful, but
not really.

00:45:10.500 --> 00:45:14.370
In England, it's the kind of a
book we keep in the smallest

00:45:14.370 --> 00:45:15.620
room in the house.

00:45:18.920 --> 00:45:20.870
English people are
famous for that.

00:45:20.870 --> 00:45:24.390
You have a little bookshelf
in the loo.

00:45:24.390 --> 00:45:25.470
We do in our house.

00:45:25.470 --> 00:45:27.990
And all my Swiss friends think
it's very strange.

00:45:27.990 --> 00:45:29.200
And my Swiss publisher--

00:45:29.200 --> 00:45:31.790
this one was published
in Switzerland--

00:45:31.790 --> 00:45:34.468
she still says, but there are
more comfortable places in the

00:45:34.468 --> 00:45:36.705
house to sit and read.

00:45:36.705 --> 00:45:38.693
But that's missing the
point entirely.

00:45:43.170 --> 00:45:47.326
So the first two, the English
version and the German

00:45:47.326 --> 00:45:49.950
version, are available
as e-books,

00:45:49.950 --> 00:45:52.250
"Swisscellany," not yet.

00:45:52.250 --> 00:45:54.850
And my new project, which I've
been working on the last two

00:45:54.850 --> 00:45:58.340
years, will come
out in October.

00:45:58.340 --> 00:46:01.791
Because this year is the 150th
anniversary of Thomas Cook

00:46:01.791 --> 00:46:04.710
coming to Switzerland, the
very first guided tour of

00:46:04.710 --> 00:46:05.870
Switzerland.

00:46:05.870 --> 00:46:08.230
And he brought a very
adventurous group here.

00:46:08.230 --> 00:46:11.460
And it was so successful that
he brought more and brought

00:46:11.460 --> 00:46:12.240
more and was brought more.

00:46:12.240 --> 00:46:14.710
And Swiss tourism exploded,
whereas before, you had to

00:46:14.710 --> 00:46:16.980
have lots of time and lots
of money to get here.

00:46:16.980 --> 00:46:19.570
It took two weeks to
get here by coach.

00:46:19.570 --> 00:46:21.795
And then suddenly, the train
line arrived, and you could

00:46:21.795 --> 00:46:23.770
get here in two days.

00:46:23.770 --> 00:46:26.710
And coming as a group
made it affordable.

00:46:26.710 --> 00:46:30.010
So it was the trains but also
Cook organizing groups that

00:46:30.010 --> 00:46:33.010
suddenly started
Swiss tourism.

00:46:33.010 --> 00:46:35.140
So Swiss tourism see it
as their birthday.

00:46:35.140 --> 00:46:38.140
So they're celebrating 150
years of Swiss tourism.

00:46:38.140 --> 00:46:42.410
And what I did is I did the
original tour that Thomas Cook

00:46:42.410 --> 00:46:43.670
did 150 years ago.

00:46:43.670 --> 00:46:46.620
Very luckily, a woman
wrote a diary.

00:46:46.620 --> 00:46:49.510
I didn't put on a big skirt
and say, I'm a lady.

00:46:49.510 --> 00:46:53.020
But I did do what they did,
going around the same places,

00:46:53.020 --> 00:46:55.750
the same itinerary, the same
overnights, same hotels where

00:46:55.750 --> 00:46:58.260
possible, to see how much
a change, see what

00:46:58.260 --> 00:46:59.160
had stayed the same.

00:46:59.160 --> 00:47:00.420
This is Switzerland.

00:47:00.420 --> 00:47:02.810
Quite a lot had stayed
the same.

00:47:02.810 --> 00:47:04.930
Change happens very
slowly here.

00:47:04.930 --> 00:47:07.372
Change would not be a winning
election theme for anyone in

00:47:07.372 --> 00:47:09.180
Switzerland.

00:47:09.180 --> 00:47:10.970
But a lot of things had
changed, obviously.

00:47:10.970 --> 00:47:14.460
And those changes, a lot of
the time, the British were

00:47:14.460 --> 00:47:16.707
involved, because the British
were too lazy to walk up

00:47:16.707 --> 00:47:19.696
mountains, so the Swiss built
trains to take them up.

00:47:19.696 --> 00:47:22.820
And they wanted bathrooms, so
the Swiss built nice hotels

00:47:22.820 --> 00:47:24.040
with bathrooms.

00:47:24.040 --> 00:47:26.620
And so a lot of the stuff
we take for granted in

00:47:26.620 --> 00:47:30.150
Switzerland, 150 years
ago, didn't exist.

00:47:30.150 --> 00:47:31.950
Switzerland was a very
poor country.

00:47:31.950 --> 00:47:34.170
There's parts of the diary where
she talks about beggars

00:47:34.170 --> 00:47:35.830
and parasites.

00:47:35.830 --> 00:47:38.370
And it reads like she's visiting
an Indian slum.

00:47:38.370 --> 00:47:41.172
But actually, she's on
the lake at Lucerne.

00:47:41.172 --> 00:47:43.140
And it's a very different
picture of Switzerland.

00:47:43.140 --> 00:47:45.305
So it was quite interesting
in that respect.

00:47:45.305 --> 00:47:47.560
That comes in October
this year.

00:47:47.560 --> 00:47:49.490
It's the anniversary.

00:47:49.490 --> 00:47:52.630
I have a website, also, where
I write once a week about

00:47:52.630 --> 00:47:53.360
Switzerland--

00:47:53.360 --> 00:47:55.190
different topics.

00:47:55.190 --> 00:47:58.690
So last week, I wrote about
these strange building poles

00:47:58.690 --> 00:48:01.856
you get on flat pieces of
land in Switzerland.

00:48:01.856 --> 00:48:03.550
The first time you come,
what are they?

00:48:03.550 --> 00:48:05.010
They look like anorexic martian

00:48:05.010 --> 00:48:06.790
spaceships have landed.

00:48:06.790 --> 00:48:09.030
And of course, they're showing
you how big the building will

00:48:09.030 --> 00:48:11.380
be that is going to be built,
because they have to by law,

00:48:11.380 --> 00:48:13.550
so that people can object
if they want.

00:48:13.550 --> 00:48:15.425
And if it's going to be a tall
building, they have these

00:48:15.425 --> 00:48:18.220
giant [INAUDIBLE] type things
with guide wires to stop them

00:48:18.220 --> 00:48:19.700
falling over.

00:48:19.700 --> 00:48:23.870
So just little things I notice
or about Swiss news.

00:48:23.870 --> 00:48:26.950
Obviously, Facebook and Twitter,
where I also talk

00:48:26.950 --> 00:48:29.430
about different Swiss things.

00:48:29.430 --> 00:48:32.210
And you're more than welcome
to have a look at them.

00:48:32.210 --> 00:48:34.230
You can contact me through
any of them or even

00:48:34.230 --> 00:48:35.850
ask a question now.

00:48:35.850 --> 00:48:37.470
And I will have some
books afterwards if

00:48:37.470 --> 00:48:38.610
you want to buy one.

00:48:38.610 --> 00:48:41.735
For those of who didn't get one,
I'm happy to sell them

00:48:41.735 --> 00:48:42.806
and sign them for you.

00:48:42.806 --> 00:48:43.792
Thank you very much.

