00:48:58.215 --> 00:48:59.995
Switzerland, or anything else.

00:48:59.995 --> 00:49:01.290
I'll bring the microphone
around.

00:49:01.290 --> 00:49:03.490
Oh, [INAUDIBLE] is setting
one up there.

00:49:03.490 --> 00:49:05.875
DICCON BEWES: You can ask
anything you want.

00:49:05.875 --> 00:49:09.060
I may not answer,
but you can ask.

00:49:09.060 --> 00:49:11.570
FEMALE SPEAKER: Great, so if
anyone else has a question,

00:49:11.570 --> 00:49:13.367
then we'll just line up
at this microphone.

00:49:13.367 --> 00:49:14.834
That'll make things
really easy.

00:49:14.834 --> 00:49:16.790
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:49:16.790 --> 00:49:21.631
I have observed that the Swiss,
in general, seem to

00:49:21.631 --> 00:49:23.873
have very beautifully taken
care of gardens.

00:49:23.873 --> 00:49:26.817
But you never seem to actually
see them in them.

00:49:26.817 --> 00:49:27.314
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:27.314 --> 00:49:29.302
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:49:29.302 --> 00:49:30.793
Have you noticed that--

00:49:30.793 --> 00:49:31.787
DICCON BEWES: It's little
elves at night.

00:49:31.787 --> 00:49:33.280
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
going on there?

00:49:33.280 --> 00:49:34.850
Are they just for show?

00:49:34.850 --> 00:49:37.710
If they have these amazing
gardens, why don't they--

00:49:37.710 --> 00:49:39.922
DICCON BEWES: Because a lot of
Swiss people don't own their

00:49:39.922 --> 00:49:41.475
own property--

00:49:41.475 --> 00:49:44.410
it's about half the ownership
rate that it is in Britain,

00:49:44.410 --> 00:49:44.880
for instance.

00:49:44.880 --> 00:49:47.835
It's about 35% here own
their own property.

00:49:47.835 --> 00:49:48.910
Most people rent.

00:49:48.910 --> 00:49:50.340
And in the cities,
it's even lower.

00:49:50.340 --> 00:49:53.600
In Bern, for instance,
it's 11% owners.

00:49:53.600 --> 00:49:56.040
So very often, it belongs to the
building, and there will

00:49:56.040 --> 00:49:59.650
be a man responsible for them.

00:49:59.650 --> 00:50:03.020
And he will come around during
the day at some point and do

00:50:03.020 --> 00:50:05.750
the garden, as well as clean
the staircase and make sure

00:50:05.750 --> 00:50:08.765
the laundry room is working and
everything, sort of like a

00:50:08.765 --> 00:50:10.200
janitor for each building.

00:50:10.200 --> 00:50:12.700
And very often, it's a man who
has retired from his normal

00:50:12.700 --> 00:50:17.325
job, and he'll have two or three
buildings to look after.

00:50:17.325 --> 00:50:20.170
But for people who do own their
own property and own

00:50:20.170 --> 00:50:23.125
their own gardens, I think
it is a labor of love.

00:50:23.125 --> 00:50:29.260
And they do do it, like most
things in Switzerland, to

00:50:29.260 --> 00:50:32.740
immense detail so that it looks
wonderful all the time.

00:50:32.740 --> 00:50:36.135
Of course, a lot of people have
what in England we call

00:50:36.135 --> 00:50:37.380
an allotment.

00:50:37.380 --> 00:50:39.710
So it's a communal
patch of land

00:50:39.710 --> 00:50:41.210
belonging to the community.

00:50:41.210 --> 00:50:44.810
And you get a small patch
which you can rent.

00:50:44.810 --> 00:50:47.895
And there are rules about what
you can and can't grow and how

00:50:47.895 --> 00:50:49.685
much thereof.

00:50:49.685 --> 00:50:52.050
And you can only have a certain
size summer house and

00:50:52.050 --> 00:50:53.072
things like that.

00:50:53.072 --> 00:50:55.560
But for many people, especially
if they live in

00:50:55.560 --> 00:50:57.770
bigger blocks or flats,
that's their escape.

00:50:57.770 --> 00:51:00.070
And they use that instead.

00:51:00.070 --> 00:51:02.950
But no, it is beautifully kept,
most of the country.

00:51:02.950 --> 00:51:05.250
I think the biggest problem
here is graffiti.

00:51:05.250 --> 00:51:06.990
You see a lot of graffiti,
far more than

00:51:06.990 --> 00:51:08.855
I ever say in England.

00:51:08.855 --> 00:51:12.730
And maybe that's just one
release for a certain part of

00:51:12.730 --> 00:51:16.700
society, because society is
quite controlled and quite

00:51:16.700 --> 00:51:18.580
perfect in many ways.

00:51:18.580 --> 00:51:23.190
The graffiti is an acceptable
way of rebelling.

00:51:23.190 --> 00:51:24.440
Thanks.

00:51:26.170 --> 00:51:26.510
Hi.

00:51:26.510 --> 00:51:27.680
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:51:27.680 --> 00:51:31.210
Just a small remark about
the car thing.

00:51:31.210 --> 00:51:34.800
The word "car" from "coach"
actually comes from French,

00:51:34.800 --> 00:51:37.960
and it seems to have been
completely independent of the

00:51:37.960 --> 00:51:39.070
English word, "car."

00:51:39.070 --> 00:51:40.200
DICCON BEWES: Yeah, it is.

00:51:40.200 --> 00:51:42.770
But the confusing thing is is
that when you're in the

00:51:42.770 --> 00:51:46.930
German-speaking part, you don't
really expect to see it.

00:51:46.930 --> 00:51:48.920
I mean, that picture
I took was in Bern.

00:51:48.920 --> 00:51:51.600
So even if you speak French, you
might think, oh well, but

00:51:51.600 --> 00:51:53.300
I'm in the German-speaking
part now.

00:51:53.300 --> 00:51:55.715
But I noticed that a
lot of Swiss German

00:51:55.715 --> 00:51:57.160
words are French words.

00:51:57.160 --> 00:51:59.360
So that when I arrived
I had schoolboy

00:51:59.360 --> 00:52:02.420
French, not very good.

00:52:02.420 --> 00:52:03.400
And I didn't have any German.

00:52:03.400 --> 00:52:05.140
But I knew what [FRENCH]

00:52:05.140 --> 00:52:05.972
and [FRENCH]

00:52:05.972 --> 00:52:09.640
meant, because they were French,
even though Swiss

00:52:09.640 --> 00:52:10.760
German speakers used them.

00:52:10.760 --> 00:52:12.830
In a menu, you only
ever see [FRENCH].

00:52:12.830 --> 00:52:15.487
It's only when you go to Germany
you realize, actually,

00:52:15.487 --> 00:52:20.370
I don't know the German word
for chicken because I never

00:52:20.370 --> 00:52:21.420
had to learn it.

00:52:21.420 --> 00:52:23.640
Or I don't actually know what
a bicycle is in German,

00:52:23.640 --> 00:52:25.820
because you can get by with
using the French.

00:52:25.820 --> 00:52:27.010
So yes, that is true.

00:52:27.010 --> 00:52:29.850
A lot of French words do creep
into Swiss German.

00:52:29.850 --> 00:52:31.248
AUDIENCE: And Italian.

00:52:31.248 --> 00:52:34.120
DICCON BEWES: And Italian.

00:52:34.120 --> 00:52:37.008
And of course, you get a lot
of Swiss men who have

00:52:37.008 --> 00:52:38.995
perfectly Italian names because
they're second or

00:52:38.995 --> 00:52:41.736
third generation, and they speak
no word of Italian and

00:52:41.736 --> 00:52:43.390
have never been to
Italy, probably.

00:52:43.390 --> 00:52:46.020
But they are Swiss Germans
with Italian names, which

00:52:46.020 --> 00:52:48.303
confuses me always when they
pop up on television.

00:52:53.213 --> 00:52:54.195
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:52:54.195 --> 00:52:55.070
DICCON BEWES: Hi.

00:52:55.070 --> 00:52:56.520
AUDIENCE: Switzerland is
one of the wealthiest

00:52:56.520 --> 00:52:59.810
countries in the world.

00:52:59.810 --> 00:53:02.590
Could you give top three
reasons for that?

00:53:07.200 --> 00:53:09.870
DICCON BEWES: I think the quick
answer is I don't know,

00:53:09.870 --> 00:53:12.660
I don't know, and
I don't know.

00:53:12.660 --> 00:53:15.900
It is a mystery, and it's one
I'm trying to come to terms

00:53:15.900 --> 00:53:18.160
with given that 150 years
ago, it was one

00:53:18.160 --> 00:53:19.820
of the poorest countries.

00:53:19.820 --> 00:53:22.440
There were pockets of wealth--

00:53:22.440 --> 00:53:23.270
Zurich, Bern.

00:53:23.270 --> 00:53:24.590
The cities with their
guilds and their

00:53:24.590 --> 00:53:26.580
traders were very wealthy.

00:53:26.580 --> 00:53:30.830
But the countryside was very
poor and really scraping a

00:53:30.830 --> 00:53:33.050
living off of the land
and nothing else.

00:53:33.050 --> 00:53:37.580
Which is why tourism was taken
on so quickly, because if

00:53:37.580 --> 00:53:41.350
you're earning one franc a day
working in the field, which is

00:53:41.350 --> 00:53:42.850
what they were-- and
that was what a

00:53:42.850 --> 00:53:45.200
breakfast cost in a hotel.

00:53:45.200 --> 00:53:47.180
So the Thomas Cook tourists
would come.

00:53:47.180 --> 00:53:49.100
And they'd pay for breakfast
what would take

00:53:49.100 --> 00:53:50.480
a whole day's wages.

00:53:50.480 --> 00:53:55.065
But if you then can earn 10
francs a week, or 5 francs a

00:53:55.065 --> 00:53:57.510
day, or whatever working in the
tourist industry, then of

00:53:57.510 --> 00:54:00.010
course, you give up the land
and move to tourism.

00:54:00.010 --> 00:54:01.300
It's partly that.

00:54:01.300 --> 00:54:05.310
It's partly the banks,
obviously.

00:54:05.310 --> 00:54:06.420
The banks have been here
for a long time.

00:54:06.420 --> 00:54:09.190
Geneva banks have been around
for hundreds of years.

00:54:09.190 --> 00:54:12.830
But banking secrecy, for all
its problems that it's now

00:54:12.830 --> 00:54:15.050
giving, did mean that a
lot of money was here.

00:54:15.050 --> 00:54:18.350
And the banks were able
to lend it out to help

00:54:18.350 --> 00:54:20.601
businesses set up.

00:54:20.601 --> 00:54:22.940
It's partly the Swiss
are very careful.

00:54:22.940 --> 00:54:24.880
They don't spend beyond their
means, generally.

00:54:24.880 --> 00:54:27.900
There's no national debt
here to speak of.

00:54:27.900 --> 00:54:30.500
And you get votes
in communities.

00:54:30.500 --> 00:54:34.640
Like Lucerne, for instance,
recently had a problem with

00:54:34.640 --> 00:54:36.440
their finances.

00:54:36.440 --> 00:54:40.230
So they voted to put up the tax
to cover the hole in the

00:54:40.230 --> 00:54:44.370
finances, which is kind of not
what most voters in other

00:54:44.370 --> 00:54:45.706
countries would do.

00:54:49.750 --> 00:54:53.585
But they see it as a
responsibility to look after

00:54:53.585 --> 00:54:56.628
their community but also
for long-term planning.

00:54:56.628 --> 00:54:59.118
So you have a lot of investment
in the train system

00:54:59.118 --> 00:54:59.900
and other things.

00:54:59.900 --> 00:55:02.020
So it is partly the Swiss
nature to be very

00:55:02.020 --> 00:55:04.200
cautious, to plan.

00:55:04.200 --> 00:55:07.590
And if you think, even when they
were farmers, they were

00:55:07.590 --> 00:55:09.390
farming in some of
worst country in

00:55:09.390 --> 00:55:11.660
Europe in terms of farmland.

00:55:11.660 --> 00:55:13.460
And yet, they still made
a living from it.

00:55:13.460 --> 00:55:17.210
So I think they're very
resourceful, very innovative,

00:55:17.210 --> 00:55:19.910
as I saw with all those
inventions.

00:55:19.910 --> 00:55:21.625
You can't invent LSD and
not become rich.

00:55:24.704 --> 00:55:27.232
Hurrah, a woman.

00:55:27.232 --> 00:55:30.118
AUDIENCE: Thank you for
confirming my theory of the

00:55:30.118 --> 00:55:33.004
little elves coming out in
the night [INAUDIBLE].

00:55:33.004 --> 00:55:34.447
It's totally what
I think happens.

00:55:34.447 --> 00:55:39.046
DICCON BEWES: It's about 3:30
AM when they come down our

00:55:39.046 --> 00:55:40.768
street, anyway.

00:55:40.768 --> 00:55:44.800
AUDIENCE: So the public
transport here and the

00:55:44.800 --> 00:55:48.380
facilities always astonish me,
because if you were to

00:55:48.380 --> 00:55:51.790
transplant that to where I come
from, it would be a wreck

00:55:51.790 --> 00:55:52.375
within a week.

00:55:52.375 --> 00:55:53.576
DICCON BEWES: Which is where?

00:55:53.576 --> 00:55:54.980
AUDIENCE: Pakistan.

00:55:54.980 --> 00:55:59.670
So you give the people the
facilities, they'll use them,

00:55:59.670 --> 00:56:04.887
they'll tear the seats apart,
they'll take whatever can be

00:56:04.887 --> 00:56:06.137
moved, et cetera.

00:56:09.180 --> 00:56:10.680
What is this attitude?

00:56:10.680 --> 00:56:13.430
How can you build an attitude
of so much respect for

00:56:13.430 --> 00:56:15.010
property that we have here?

00:56:15.010 --> 00:56:17.400
You said hundreds of years
ago, they were very poor.

00:56:17.400 --> 00:56:19.812
Did they have the same attitude
then as well?

00:56:19.812 --> 00:56:21.100
DICCON BEWES: Probably.

00:56:21.100 --> 00:56:22.330
I mean, I think it's
two things.

00:56:22.330 --> 00:56:25.080
One, it's partly the trust that
I talked about, that they

00:56:25.080 --> 00:56:28.810
trust each other to
behave properly.

00:56:28.810 --> 00:56:32.190
But it's also the fact that
because the system, from the

00:56:32.190 --> 00:56:36.200
very beginning, from 1291, when
Switzerland was founded,

00:56:36.200 --> 00:56:38.668
it was three cantons together.

00:56:38.668 --> 00:56:41.590
They'd never had a president
who's had any power.

00:56:41.590 --> 00:56:44.025
They have a president who
changes every year to shake

00:56:44.025 --> 00:56:45.486
hands but doesn't
have any power.

00:56:45.486 --> 00:56:46.947
They've never had an emperor.

00:56:46.947 --> 00:56:48.895
They've never had a
military governor.

00:56:48.895 --> 00:56:52.520
They've never had any form of
central control, really.

00:56:52.520 --> 00:56:53.990
Napoleon came.

00:56:53.990 --> 00:56:56.015
He tried, he failed, he went.

00:56:56.015 --> 00:56:59.130
A bit like the story of
Napoleon, really.

00:56:59.130 --> 00:57:00.700
And it was the same
in Switzerland.

00:57:00.700 --> 00:57:02.090
He invaded, he conquered.

00:57:02.090 --> 00:57:04.110
He set up the Helvetic
Republic.

00:57:04.110 --> 00:57:06.650
It lasted five years, because
the Swiss just couldn't deal

00:57:06.650 --> 00:57:08.100
with central control.

00:57:08.100 --> 00:57:10.600
And because they've always
had a sense of,

00:57:10.600 --> 00:57:12.640
we are in this together.

00:57:12.640 --> 00:57:15.450
We are a community, whether
we're three cantons or 23

00:57:15.450 --> 00:57:17.290
cantons or eight
million people.

00:57:17.290 --> 00:57:20.430
And so if you make a mess
of the train, then I

00:57:20.430 --> 00:57:22.420
have to pay for it.

00:57:22.420 --> 00:57:27.160
And so if there's that sense
of communal responsibility,

00:57:27.160 --> 00:57:30.780
which possibly used to be there
in other countries-- my

00:57:30.780 --> 00:57:35.210
parents talk about Britain in
the 1950s as if it was some

00:57:35.210 --> 00:57:37.060
sort of utopia, which
I'm sure it wasn't.

00:57:37.060 --> 00:57:41.570
But there is that feeling that
Switzerland sometimes is the

00:57:41.570 --> 00:57:44.940
same as another country was
maybe 30 years ago.

00:57:44.940 --> 00:57:49.670
And so there's still that
feeling of community here.

00:57:49.670 --> 00:57:53.440
And if you have a problem, or if
someone wrecks the trains,

00:57:53.440 --> 00:57:55.940
then it can be decided by the
people what happens in terms

00:57:55.940 --> 00:57:58.305
of, does the train company
get more money?

00:57:58.305 --> 00:58:00.200
Because at every level--

00:58:00.200 --> 00:58:03.120
community, canton,
or country--

00:58:03.120 --> 00:58:04.850
the people can decide.

00:58:04.850 --> 00:58:08.830
So in Bern, for instance, we
recently voted on should we

00:58:08.830 --> 00:58:11.990
extend the tram line
out to the suburbs.

00:58:11.990 --> 00:58:14.000
Where else in the world would
you vote on that sort of

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:14.590
minute detail?

00:58:14.590 --> 00:58:20.790
Or should we build bus stops
with a roof over them of not?

00:58:20.790 --> 00:58:23.130
Or should we extend opening
hours to 8 o'clock

00:58:23.130 --> 00:58:25.010
instead of 7 o'clock?

00:58:25.010 --> 00:58:26.360
And things like that.

00:58:26.360 --> 00:58:29.110
It sounds like very detailed,
boring stuff.

00:58:29.110 --> 00:58:30.730
And sometimes, it is.

00:58:30.730 --> 00:58:33.850
But if the people are asked all
the time what they think,

00:58:33.850 --> 00:58:37.140
and the rules are made by the
people, then I think there is

00:58:37.140 --> 00:58:41.252
a bigger sense of communal
responsibility than if they're

00:58:41.252 --> 00:58:43.682
told what to do.

00:58:43.682 --> 00:58:46.112
It's just a theory.

00:58:46.112 --> 00:58:46.610
Hi.

00:58:46.610 --> 00:58:47.917
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:58:47.917 --> 00:58:52.490
I'd be curious, since you only
hear an outsider's view of

00:58:52.490 --> 00:58:55.465
Switzerland, I'm curious what
Switzerland thinks of all its

00:58:55.465 --> 00:58:59.012
outsiders here in the country
and if we're changing the

00:58:59.012 --> 00:59:01.630
country or they're changing
us, sort of that whole

00:59:01.630 --> 00:59:02.660
[INAUDIBLE].

00:59:02.660 --> 00:59:05.135
DICCON BEWES: Oh, how diplomatic
should I be?

00:59:08.105 --> 00:59:13.460
I think as in any country,
you will have a divide--

00:59:13.460 --> 00:59:15.340
typically a left-right
divide--

00:59:15.340 --> 00:59:17.340
on the view.

00:59:17.340 --> 00:59:22.260
When I first arrived in 2005,
the first election campaign I

00:59:22.260 --> 00:59:25.630
experienced was the one with the
black sheep, the one that

00:59:25.630 --> 00:59:29.180
would be classed as racist in
Britain, with three white

00:59:29.180 --> 00:59:32.920
sheep kicking a black sheep
off the Swiss flag.

00:59:32.920 --> 00:59:37.300
Now, of course, even my not
right-wing Swiss friends say,

00:59:37.300 --> 00:59:38.960
well, it's just turn of
phrase, the black

00:59:38.960 --> 00:59:40.060
sheep of the family.

00:59:40.060 --> 00:59:43.590
But for me, it was overtly
racist and

00:59:43.590 --> 00:59:46.280
shouldn't have been allowed.

00:59:46.280 --> 00:59:51.290
And I think it fostered a
climate of latent xenophobia,

00:59:51.290 --> 00:59:53.100
even if you're white
and Christian,

00:59:53.100 --> 00:59:55.910
an acceptable immigrant.

00:59:55.910 --> 01:00:00.970
I have still experienced
insults, abuse, because I

01:00:00.970 --> 01:00:03.610
speak high German, although my
German isn't so high anymore.

01:00:03.610 --> 01:00:06.090
It's a bit polluted.

01:00:06.090 --> 01:00:08.410
But in the shop, people would
speak to me in Swiss German,

01:00:08.410 --> 01:00:09.830
and I'd reply in high German.

01:00:09.830 --> 01:00:12.710
And a couple of people got so
angry we had to call the

01:00:12.710 --> 01:00:17.810
police because I was speaking
that Nazi language.

01:00:17.810 --> 01:00:21.090
But you get that in any
society, of course.

01:00:21.090 --> 01:00:22.840
There's intolerance.

01:00:22.840 --> 01:00:27.160
But I think here, it's accepted
by the general

01:00:27.160 --> 01:00:30.110
populace in a way that I don't
think is acceptable.

01:00:30.110 --> 01:00:34.660
So therefore, what in other
countries would be passed as

01:00:34.660 --> 01:00:37.820
extreme becomes mainstream
here.

01:00:37.820 --> 01:00:40.200
And I've noticed that over
the last few years.

01:00:40.200 --> 01:00:43.350
And of course, it is exacerbated
by the increasing

01:00:43.350 --> 01:00:44.430
number of immigrants.

01:00:44.430 --> 01:00:47.486
Since Switzerland joined
the [INAUDIBLE]

01:00:47.486 --> 01:00:51.830
area and free movements of
people within the EU, despite

01:00:51.830 --> 01:00:55.405
not being an EU member, a lot
of Germans, especially, have

01:00:55.405 --> 01:00:57.150
moved here.

01:00:57.150 --> 01:01:01.290
And in Zurich and Zug, you hear
a lot of German voices.

01:01:01.290 --> 01:01:02.951
And to me, that's wonderful,
because I can

01:01:02.951 --> 01:01:06.090
understand them perfectly.

01:01:06.090 --> 01:01:09.430
But I can understand also why
a lot of Swiss people--

01:01:09.430 --> 01:01:11.170
Swiss Germans--

01:01:11.170 --> 01:01:13.610
feel insecure about that.

01:01:13.610 --> 01:01:16.325
There's this big love-hate
relationship between

01:01:16.325 --> 01:01:17.720
Switzerland and Germany.

01:01:17.720 --> 01:01:19.780
It's a bit like Canada
and America, only

01:01:19.780 --> 01:01:21.720
the other way up.

01:01:21.720 --> 01:01:24.530
It's like they're taking
over our culture.

01:01:24.530 --> 01:01:26.560
We're different from
them, but we speak

01:01:26.560 --> 01:01:27.600
roughly the same language.

01:01:27.600 --> 01:01:28.240
Is it a dialect?

01:01:28.240 --> 01:01:28.860
Is it a language?

01:01:28.860 --> 01:01:30.800
Is it an accent?

01:01:30.800 --> 01:01:34.500
And it's all to do with Swiss
national identity.

01:01:34.500 --> 01:01:38.103
And then, of course, you just
have the fact that Switzerland

01:01:38.103 --> 01:01:39.830
never had an empire.

01:01:39.830 --> 01:01:44.490
So whereas Britain has had
centuries of immigration from

01:01:44.490 --> 01:01:48.150
different cultures, different
races, different religions, in

01:01:48.150 --> 01:01:50.320
Switzerland, it's a
fairly new thing.

01:01:50.320 --> 01:01:52.850
Even the immigrants in the '60s
were Catholic and white

01:01:52.850 --> 01:01:55.295
because they were Italian or
Portuguese or Spanish.

01:01:55.295 --> 01:01:58.660
And then in the '90s came white
Muslims from the former

01:01:58.660 --> 01:02:00.036
Yugoslavia.

01:02:00.036 --> 01:02:02.860
And so it is a new thing for
Switzerland to have to deal

01:02:02.860 --> 01:02:05.324
with multiculturalism.

01:02:05.324 --> 01:02:07.700
And that's why you have a lot
of insecurities about

01:02:07.700 --> 01:02:10.800
minarets, about wearing the
burka in public, about

01:02:10.800 --> 01:02:12.650
swimming lessons for girls.

01:02:12.650 --> 01:02:16.850
And it's a very public debate,
which is good.

01:02:16.850 --> 01:02:19.205
And it's probably more of a
debate than you would get

01:02:19.205 --> 01:02:21.290
about it in Britain, because
things are decided by

01:02:21.290 --> 01:02:22.710
referendum.

01:02:22.710 --> 01:02:25.280
But that being said, because
it's a public debate, you

01:02:25.280 --> 01:02:28.490
sometimes hear and see things
which you think, actually, I

01:02:28.490 --> 01:02:31.910
don't want to hear
and see that.

01:02:31.910 --> 01:02:33.120
It's an interesting situation.

01:02:33.120 --> 01:02:34.910
It's sometimes uncomfortable.

01:02:34.910 --> 01:02:37.290
As a foreigner here, I
feel uncomfortable.

01:02:37.290 --> 01:02:40.270
And sometimes, I feel
more than welcome.

01:02:40.270 --> 01:02:44.565
Learning the language changed
everything, except when I go

01:02:44.565 --> 01:02:47.690
to Neuchatel somewhere
and then have to

01:02:47.690 --> 01:02:50.100
speak my awful French.

01:02:50.100 --> 01:02:52.180
But learning German has
obviously made a difference,

01:02:52.180 --> 01:02:55.250
because then people actually
know you are making the effort

01:02:55.250 --> 01:02:55.940
to integrate.

01:02:55.940 --> 01:02:59.180
Integration is a two-way street,
as far as I see it.

01:02:59.180 --> 01:03:00.270
Hi.

01:03:00.270 --> 01:03:01.610
AUDIENCE: Hi.

01:03:01.610 --> 01:03:04.490
I'm just curious to know how
much of the things you were

01:03:04.490 --> 01:03:05.280
talking about--

01:03:05.280 --> 01:03:09.667
like spontaneity and the habits
in parties and things

01:03:09.667 --> 01:03:12.600
like that-- apply also to the
French and the Italian

01:03:12.600 --> 01:03:14.950
cantons, if at all.

01:03:14.950 --> 01:03:19.180
DICCON BEWES: They do
to a certain extent.

01:03:19.180 --> 01:03:22.770
I think the interesting thing is
when I go and give talks in

01:03:22.770 --> 01:03:25.720
Lugano and Lausanne, which are
not the same place, by the

01:03:25.720 --> 01:03:28.740
way, with different names,
as someone once asked me.

01:03:28.740 --> 01:03:31.795
Is Lucerne, Lausanne and Lugano,
is that just all the

01:03:31.795 --> 01:03:34.980
same place with German, French,
and Italian names?

01:03:38.900 --> 01:03:39.910
It's kind of logical.

01:03:39.910 --> 01:03:41.620
Genf is Geneva is Ginevra.

01:03:41.620 --> 01:03:43.310
They all change.

01:03:43.310 --> 01:03:45.910
But I think the interesting
thing is when I go and give

01:03:45.910 --> 01:03:49.310
talks in the Swiss [INAUDIBLE]
in Ticino, the Swiss people

01:03:49.310 --> 01:03:52.130
there say, oh, and of course,
that's German-speaking

01:03:52.130 --> 01:03:52.450
Switzerland.

01:03:52.450 --> 01:03:54.400
That's not us.

01:03:54.400 --> 01:03:58.450
But the expats living there,
almost all of them say, this

01:03:58.450 --> 01:04:02.930
is my life, just in French
instead of German.

01:04:02.930 --> 01:04:04.750
And it's partly a perception
thing.

01:04:04.750 --> 01:04:08.295
It's partly the Italian
and French--

01:04:08.295 --> 01:04:10.927
and we mustn't forget the
14 Romansh speakers in

01:04:10.927 --> 01:04:12.177
Graubunden.

01:04:14.910 --> 01:04:16.310
They want to be part
of Switzerland.

01:04:16.310 --> 01:04:18.600
They don't want to be part of
France or Italy, because they

01:04:18.600 --> 01:04:21.580
know they would just be another
ignored province and

01:04:21.580 --> 01:04:22.270
totally forgotten about.

01:04:22.270 --> 01:04:24.188
Whereas in Switzerland,
they have a role.

01:04:24.188 --> 01:04:28.720
They have a voice, which they
wouldn't have if they were in

01:04:28.720 --> 01:04:30.670
their respective language
countries.

01:04:30.670 --> 01:04:34.545
So they want to be part, but
they still feel like a

01:04:34.545 --> 01:04:35.910
minority, because they
are a minority.

01:04:35.910 --> 01:04:39.500
65% of the population
is German speaking.

01:04:39.500 --> 01:04:41.445
And so they want to feel
like they're different.

01:04:41.445 --> 01:04:42.815
And of course, there
are differences.

01:04:42.815 --> 01:04:44.750
There are differences
in every country.

01:04:44.750 --> 01:04:48.220
If I go to the north of
England, I don't even

01:04:48.220 --> 01:04:49.936
understand what they're
saying.

01:04:49.936 --> 01:04:53.070
Spend the day in Newcastle,
and I'm lost.

01:04:53.070 --> 01:04:56.037
And there are very big
differences in any country.

01:04:56.037 --> 01:04:58.422
And here, the differences
appear bigger

01:04:58.422 --> 01:05:00.330
because of the language.

01:05:00.330 --> 01:05:04.060
And I think, actually, from an
outsider's point of view, the

01:05:04.060 --> 01:05:06.320
differences are much smaller.

01:05:06.320 --> 01:05:07.640
They're still there.

01:05:07.640 --> 01:05:12.740
So for instance, you can quite
easily go out for a business

01:05:12.740 --> 01:05:15.820
lunch, as I have done, in the
French-speaking part, and

01:05:15.820 --> 01:05:17.120
everyone will drink wine.

01:05:17.120 --> 01:05:19.577
Which here, doesn't normally
happen so much, because we all

01:05:19.577 --> 01:05:21.625
know we'll fall asleep
during the afternoon.

01:05:24.340 --> 01:05:27.290
But you still get the thing
where people in

01:05:27.290 --> 01:05:28.996
Geneva contact me--

01:05:28.996 --> 01:05:31.940
I've lived here four or five
years, and still, my Swiss

01:05:31.940 --> 01:05:34.690
neighbors haven't really
said more than hello.

01:05:34.690 --> 01:05:38.182
So it's still breaking through
that clique, breaking through

01:05:38.182 --> 01:05:39.590
that coconut.

01:05:39.590 --> 01:05:42.720
And so every town can
be different.

01:05:42.720 --> 01:05:44.780
And I get emails from people,
why didn't you

01:05:44.780 --> 01:05:45.810
talk about my village?

01:05:45.810 --> 01:05:47.658
It's so different.

01:05:47.658 --> 01:05:49.660
It's like, I'm really
sorry I couldn't

01:05:49.660 --> 01:05:50.510
talk about every village.

01:05:50.510 --> 01:05:51.780
It's not a guidebook.

01:05:51.780 --> 01:05:53.380
And of course, there
are differences.

01:05:53.380 --> 01:05:58.560
But I would say as a general
rule, what makes the Swiss

01:05:58.560 --> 01:06:00.630
Swiss applies in all areas.

01:06:00.630 --> 01:06:05.555
Otherwise, they would feel
French and seem French and not

01:06:05.555 --> 01:06:06.805
just speak French.

01:06:11.703 --> 01:06:12.689
Oh, dear.

01:06:12.689 --> 01:06:14.661
A second question.

01:06:14.661 --> 01:06:16.180
I must have said something
wrong.

01:06:16.180 --> 01:06:18.835
AUDIENCE: When speaking of
languages, why do you think a

01:06:18.835 --> 01:06:24.290
country that has four official
languages works in

01:06:24.290 --> 01:06:27.510
Switzerland, whereas, for
example, it doesn't work in,

01:06:27.510 --> 01:06:28.710
say, Belgium?

01:06:28.710 --> 01:06:32.730
DICCON BEWES: Well firstly, I
should point out that Romansh

01:06:32.730 --> 01:06:35.680
is a national language, not
an official language.

01:06:35.680 --> 01:06:39.870
It's a typically Swiss
hair-splitting definition.

01:06:39.870 --> 01:06:42.850
But it means that it's a
national language, but all

01:06:42.850 --> 01:06:44.510
documents and everything
and signs don't

01:06:44.510 --> 01:06:46.100
have to be in Romansh.

01:06:46.100 --> 01:06:49.300
So if you get official stuff on
the government website, for

01:06:49.300 --> 01:06:51.260
instance, it doesn't have
to be in Romansh.

01:06:51.260 --> 01:06:53.731
But if they're dealing with a
Romansh speaker, then they

01:06:53.731 --> 01:06:54.840
have to do it in Romansh.

01:06:54.840 --> 01:06:55.540
It is a national language.

01:06:55.540 --> 01:06:57.470
But it's only been a national
language since a referendum

01:06:57.470 --> 01:07:00.480
decided that in about 1935.

01:07:00.480 --> 01:07:02.570
I think here, it is
interesting as to

01:07:02.570 --> 01:07:04.200
how they can coexist.

01:07:04.200 --> 01:07:06.850
Partly, they all had to learn
one of the other languages in

01:07:06.850 --> 01:07:09.200
school, as well as learning
English as well.

01:07:09.200 --> 01:07:12.252
And there's a big debate as to
which should come first.

01:07:12.252 --> 01:07:15.720
And partly, it's again that
sense of community.

01:07:15.720 --> 01:07:18.580
We all choose to be together
as a country.

01:07:18.580 --> 01:07:21.560
So we all have to get along,
even though we speak different

01:07:21.560 --> 01:07:23.922
languages, because if we didn't,
we would fall apart,

01:07:23.922 --> 01:07:25.172
like Belgium.

01:07:27.510 --> 01:07:31.135
But what they do is
make it very easy.

01:07:31.135 --> 01:07:34.220
So in Parliament, you can speak
in your own language.

01:07:34.220 --> 01:07:38.743
And the presumption is is that
people will understand.

01:07:38.743 --> 01:07:41.378
And if they don't, it's their
fault, because they haven't

01:07:41.378 --> 01:07:43.850
learned your language.

01:07:43.850 --> 01:07:45.640
And so there is that
presumption.

01:07:45.640 --> 01:07:48.860
I find the further
you get away--

01:07:48.860 --> 01:07:51.340
it's called the Rostigraben, the
divide between the German

01:07:51.340 --> 01:07:54.439
and the French bit, because the
Germans speak [INAUDIBLE]

01:07:54.439 --> 01:07:57.433
and the French speak as
[INAUDIBLE], basically.

01:07:57.433 --> 01:07:59.429
Oversimplification.

01:07:59.429 --> 01:08:00.830
But it's called the
Rostigraben.

01:08:00.830 --> 01:08:05.520
And the further east you get
from it, the less likely you

01:08:05.520 --> 01:08:06.870
are to get by in French.

01:08:06.870 --> 01:08:08.910
So in Bern, you can get by in
French and in [INAUDIBLE]

01:08:08.910 --> 01:08:13.325
almost not at all, whereas
the same applies.

01:08:13.325 --> 01:08:15.550
Gregor, my boyfriend,
speaks no French.

01:08:15.550 --> 01:08:17.979
He grew up in Liechtenstein,
so he learned English.

01:08:17.979 --> 01:08:21.840
So as soon as we cross the
imaginary border, he can get

01:08:21.840 --> 01:08:24.149
by in German in Fribourg,
for instance,

01:08:24.149 --> 01:08:26.540
because it's almost bilingual.

01:08:26.540 --> 01:08:28.960
But as soon as we get further
into the French-speaking part,

01:08:28.960 --> 01:08:30.924
they actually will speak
English with

01:08:30.924 --> 01:08:33.319
you rather than German.

01:08:33.319 --> 01:08:35.630
And he'll say something in Swiss
German, and they'll say,

01:08:35.630 --> 01:08:37.050
oh, I don't speak
that language.

01:08:37.050 --> 01:08:38.370
And I say something in
English or my bad

01:08:38.370 --> 01:08:40.420
French, and it's fine.

01:08:40.420 --> 01:08:42.744
And of course, you can go to
Geneva and speak English

01:08:42.744 --> 01:08:46.165
almost everywhere, because a
third of the population is not

01:08:46.165 --> 01:08:48.229
even Swiss.

01:08:48.229 --> 01:08:54.149
But I think it is-- it's an
interesting conundrum, two

01:08:54.149 --> 01:08:55.509
religions as well.

01:08:55.509 --> 01:08:58.479
And the last war of religion was
1847 with the Sonderbund

01:08:58.479 --> 01:08:59.416
[INAUDIBLE].

01:08:59.416 --> 01:09:03.000
How come they can get along
with four languages, two

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:07.649
religions, 13 parties
in Parliament?

01:09:07.649 --> 01:09:08.939
And yet, it still functions.

01:09:08.939 --> 01:09:13.630
And it's partly to do with
everyone is included all the

01:09:13.630 --> 01:09:15.720
time or has the chance
to be included.

01:09:15.720 --> 01:09:17.438
Not everyone is included,
because a lot of

01:09:17.438 --> 01:09:18.666
people don't bother.

01:09:18.666 --> 01:09:21.612
And obviously, none of the
foreigners can be included,

01:09:21.612 --> 01:09:23.470
because we don't count
in electoral

01:09:23.470 --> 01:09:25.650
terms, political terms.

01:09:25.650 --> 01:09:28.470
But everyone has the chance
to have their voice heard.

01:09:28.470 --> 01:09:30.870
No one can say, I
wasn't asked.

01:09:30.870 --> 01:09:32.670
No one can say, I'm
not important.

01:09:32.670 --> 01:09:34.862
What I think isn't important.

01:09:34.862 --> 01:09:38.210
And so you always have that
chance to have your voice

01:09:38.210 --> 01:09:43.172
heard, which I think is possibly
what makes it work.

01:09:43.172 --> 01:09:46.796
In Germany, you say [GERMAN],
which means a nation that is

01:09:46.796 --> 01:09:48.240
only held together because
they have the

01:09:48.240 --> 01:09:50.120
will to be held together.

01:09:50.120 --> 01:09:52.899
It's much easier in German.

01:09:52.899 --> 01:09:56.010
They exist because they want
to, not because of

01:09:56.010 --> 01:09:58.508
geographical boundaries or
political boundaries or

01:09:58.508 --> 01:10:00.745
religious boundaries or
language boundaries.

01:10:00.745 --> 01:10:02.453
They exist because
they want to.

01:10:05.840 --> 01:10:08.200
This side of the room
is being very quiet.

01:10:08.200 --> 01:10:10.853
I'm not leaving until we get one
question from over here.

01:10:14.304 --> 01:10:17.262
Well, that worked.

01:10:17.262 --> 01:10:17.755
Hi.

01:10:17.755 --> 01:10:19.420
AUDIENCE: Hi, my
name is Pascal.

01:10:19.420 --> 01:10:20.176
DICCON BEWES: I know.

01:10:20.176 --> 01:10:21.128
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:10:21.128 --> 01:10:22.560
So much for my nationality.

01:10:22.560 --> 01:10:26.495
No, I was actually wondering
if you have noticed any

01:10:26.495 --> 01:10:29.541
particularities when the Swiss
is actually outside of the

01:10:29.541 --> 01:10:32.668
coconut, when he goes
[INAUDIBLE]?

01:10:32.668 --> 01:10:34.320
DICCON BEWES: You mean
outside Switzerland?

01:10:34.320 --> 01:10:36.230
AUDIENCE: Yeah, when he
goes abroad, is he--

01:10:36.230 --> 01:10:37.160
DICCON BEWES: He
becomes Swiss.

01:10:37.160 --> 01:10:38.556
AUDIENCE: He's probably
easy spottable.

01:10:38.556 --> 01:10:40.420
DICCON BEWES: Basically,
he becomes Swiss.

01:10:40.420 --> 01:10:44.443
There is a famous saying that a
Swiss is only Swiss when he

01:10:44.443 --> 01:10:45.660
leaves the country.

01:10:45.660 --> 01:10:48.450
And when he's in Switzerland,
he's Bernese or

01:10:48.450 --> 01:10:51.174
Ticinese or a Thurgauer.

01:10:51.174 --> 01:10:54.170
And so you're only Swiss when
you leave, because when you're

01:10:54.170 --> 01:10:56.780
here, your canton is
more important.

01:10:56.780 --> 01:10:59.950
Because Switzerland, as an
entity, is only 150 years old,

01:10:59.950 --> 01:11:00.683
roughly 1848.

01:11:00.683 --> 01:11:05.650
Before then, it really was a
confederation of individual

01:11:05.650 --> 01:11:07.750
almost city-states or
country-states.

01:11:07.750 --> 01:11:08.430
I call it an island.

01:11:08.430 --> 01:11:11.190
It was really more like
an archipelago.

01:11:11.190 --> 01:11:13.790
And sometimes, it feels like
26 little countries roughly

01:11:13.790 --> 01:11:16.840
going in the same direction,
because each canton has its

01:11:16.840 --> 01:11:20.780
own laws and flags and police
and education system and tax.

01:11:20.780 --> 01:11:23.890
It's a bit like the states in
America but even more so.

01:11:23.890 --> 01:11:27.020
So I think Swiss people
can become more Swiss

01:11:27.020 --> 01:11:27.910
when they're abroad.

01:11:27.910 --> 01:11:29.880
And they actually talk to other
Swiss people much more

01:11:29.880 --> 01:11:33.260
willingly than they do when
they're in Switzerland.

01:11:33.260 --> 01:11:37.750
And they become much more house
proud about Switzerland

01:11:37.750 --> 01:11:45.445
and become a little bit less
accepting of criticism than

01:11:45.445 --> 01:11:47.710
they would from people
who are actually

01:11:47.710 --> 01:11:49.470
living here, for instance.

01:11:49.470 --> 01:11:52.440
But I think that's the case
for a lot of people

01:11:52.440 --> 01:11:53.898
when they go abroad.

01:11:53.898 --> 01:11:56.465
They defend their country a lot
more than they would at

01:11:56.465 --> 01:11:57.270
home, obviously.

01:11:57.270 --> 01:12:02.340
And also, Swiss expats, the
so-called "fifth Switzerland."

01:12:02.340 --> 01:12:04.340
You have the four national
languages here, and then the

01:12:04.340 --> 01:12:07.080
fifth is all the Swiss
living abroad.

01:12:07.080 --> 01:12:10.860
Some of them, I get emails from
them saying either, oh,

01:12:10.860 --> 01:12:13.315
it made me so homesick.

01:12:13.315 --> 01:12:14.800
That's just what I remember.

01:12:14.800 --> 01:12:16.880
And when I visit my family
and everything,

01:12:16.880 --> 01:12:17.270
it's just how it is.

01:12:17.270 --> 01:12:19.470
And then others say, you're
got it completely wrong,

01:12:19.470 --> 01:12:22.560
because they are remembering,
little bit rose colored, what

01:12:22.560 --> 01:12:25.341
Switzerland was like
before they left.

01:12:25.341 --> 01:12:28.420
And so they feel the urge to
defend it if they feel I'm

01:12:28.420 --> 01:12:29.860
being too critical.

01:12:29.860 --> 01:12:33.465
But I think that's true of
almost any nationality abroad.

01:12:33.465 --> 01:12:36.090
I don't think the Swiss are
actually any different.

01:12:36.090 --> 01:12:37.770
When they're outside
the coconut,

01:12:37.770 --> 01:12:39.310
they become more peachy.

01:12:42.210 --> 01:12:43.460
Still waiting.

01:12:46.064 --> 01:12:47.314
A questioner.

01:12:51.443 --> 01:12:53.888
See now, we're all going
to watch you walk.

01:12:53.888 --> 01:12:55.138
It's here.

01:12:58.790 --> 01:12:59.320
It'd better be worth it.

01:12:59.320 --> 01:13:04.776
AUDIENCE: The very left edge
of the room, as you wanted.

01:13:04.776 --> 01:13:11.540
So first thing, please assure
me if I understood well.

01:13:11.540 --> 01:13:18.740
In the beginning, Swiss people
are not asking questions which

01:13:18.740 --> 01:13:22.090
