me, for example, right?

01:13:22.090 --> 01:13:23.340
So not--

01:13:25.255 --> 01:13:26.580
DICCON BEWES: Invading
your privacy.

01:13:26.580 --> 01:13:29.580
AUDIENCE: Violate my
coconut, right?

01:13:29.580 --> 01:13:30.075
So how--

01:13:30.075 --> 01:13:36.015
[LAUGHTER]

01:13:36.015 --> 01:13:39.975
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
coconut [INAUDIBLE]

01:13:39.975 --> 01:13:42.770
as well, right?

01:13:42.770 --> 01:13:45.584
DICCON BEWES: Mental image was
very, very [INAUDIBLE].

01:13:45.584 --> 01:13:46.520
[LAUGHTER]

01:13:46.520 --> 01:13:48.960
DICCON BEWES: Better than
violating your peach, I think.

01:13:51.930 --> 01:13:53.415
AUDIENCE: Whatever you like.

01:13:53.415 --> 01:13:55.890
DICCON BEWES: Yes, OK.

01:13:55.890 --> 01:13:58.860
Pick a fruit, any fruit.

01:13:58.860 --> 01:14:00.345
Not the banana, please.

01:14:00.345 --> 01:14:04.800
[LAUGHTER]

01:14:04.800 --> 01:14:06.285
AUDIENCE: OK, and--

01:14:06.285 --> 01:14:07.770
DICCON BEWES: And
the question.

01:14:07.770 --> 01:14:13.540
AUDIENCE: So the question is,
how they dare to ask private

01:14:13.540 --> 01:14:17.178
questions when you want to
rent a flat, they ask

01:14:17.178 --> 01:14:18.480
[INAUDIBLE].

01:14:18.480 --> 01:14:21.980
Depending on who you meet,
they go in more or less

01:14:21.980 --> 01:14:23.460
private stuff, right?

01:14:23.460 --> 01:14:28.300
And they are ready to reject
you once you don't want to

01:14:28.300 --> 01:14:30.540
share some private
information.

01:14:30.540 --> 01:14:31.750
They ask about--

01:14:31.750 --> 01:14:34.441
DICCON BEWES: I think that's--

01:14:34.441 --> 01:14:37.450
AUDIENCE: In my country, I feel
violated with many of

01:14:37.450 --> 01:14:41.328
those questions that I see on
those forms and when I am

01:14:41.328 --> 01:14:44.304
asked in my face when
I look for a flat.

01:14:44.304 --> 01:14:46.075
And how does it go
[INAUDIBLE]?

01:14:46.075 --> 01:14:46.920
DICCON BEWES: I think--

01:14:46.920 --> 01:14:49.684
I've been lucky in that I've
never had to look for a flat

01:14:49.684 --> 01:14:52.120
here, thank goodness.

01:14:52.120 --> 01:14:54.140
It's party a difference
between business--

01:14:54.140 --> 01:14:55.050
AUDIENCE: Lucky you.

01:14:55.050 --> 01:14:57.290
DICCON BEWES: Yes.

01:14:57.290 --> 01:14:59.050
Renting a flat is a business
thing, rather

01:14:59.050 --> 01:15:00.400
than a social thing.

01:15:00.400 --> 01:15:02.580
So different rules apply.

01:15:02.580 --> 01:15:05.660
And it's also they want to
be sure that you are an

01:15:05.660 --> 01:15:08.530
upstanding person, because you
are going to be living in

01:15:08.530 --> 01:15:09.930
their property.

01:15:09.930 --> 01:15:13.160
And so they ask you what they
probably think of as moral

01:15:13.160 --> 01:15:16.230
questions, like do you do
drugs, or whatever.

01:15:16.230 --> 01:15:17.410
I don't know what
they ask you.

01:15:17.410 --> 01:15:22.420
But it's also a question here
of sometimes political

01:15:22.420 --> 01:15:26.215
correctness or that
privacy boundaries

01:15:26.215 --> 01:15:27.400
don't actually apply.

01:15:27.400 --> 01:15:29.830
I have a friend who applied--

01:15:29.830 --> 01:15:33.220
she was working in a company
already, and she

01:15:33.220 --> 01:15:34.470
applied for a promotion.

01:15:37.020 --> 01:15:39.700
She's a 30-year-old
woman, married.

01:15:39.700 --> 01:15:41.790
In her interview, they asked
her, so when are you planning

01:15:41.790 --> 01:15:42.886
to have children?

01:15:42.886 --> 01:15:45.600
Now, in England, that kind of
question would be illegal,

01:15:45.600 --> 01:15:47.200
because it's nothing
to do with her

01:15:47.200 --> 01:15:48.810
ability to do the job.

01:15:48.810 --> 01:15:53.170
But as far as the employer is
concerned, it is, look, are

01:15:53.170 --> 01:15:56.080
you a good risk for the next
three years or whatever?

01:15:56.080 --> 01:15:58.240
So those kind of what we think
of as very personal

01:15:58.240 --> 01:15:59.530
questions--

01:15:59.530 --> 01:16:03.570
maybe personal questions about
your lifestyle, for instance--

01:16:03.570 --> 01:16:06.640
are actually, in the Swiss
eyes, seen as practical

01:16:06.640 --> 01:16:11.810
questions to determine whether
to go ahead or not for a

01:16:11.810 --> 01:16:12.840
longer term.

01:16:12.840 --> 01:16:18.030
I know it's a very two sides of
one coin, and sometimes it

01:16:18.030 --> 01:16:19.780
can feel very invasive.

01:16:19.780 --> 01:16:23.820
Like for instance when I applied
for jobs here, first

01:16:23.820 --> 01:16:26.330
thing my boyfriend says is,
well, your CV hasn't got a

01:16:26.330 --> 01:16:29.470
picture on it, because
pretty much, CVs here

01:16:29.470 --> 01:16:30.620
have pictures on them.

01:16:30.620 --> 01:16:33.870
And I said, well, what I look
like has nothing to do with my

01:16:33.870 --> 01:16:34.970
ability to do the job.

01:16:34.970 --> 01:16:36.970
He said, yes, but how will
they know if you fit in?

01:16:39.470 --> 01:16:41.470
Well, exactly.

01:16:41.470 --> 01:16:44.640
Whether I fit in or not has to
do with whether I'm qualified

01:16:44.640 --> 01:16:47.305
or whether I'm experienced
enough to do the job, not

01:16:47.305 --> 01:16:50.710
whether I'm male or
black or whatever.

01:16:50.710 --> 01:16:53.810
And so there are different
rules.

01:16:53.810 --> 01:16:58.050
And I think if you come from a
society which has slightly

01:16:58.050 --> 01:17:00.520
different expectations
and rules, it

01:17:00.520 --> 01:17:01.910
can seem very intrusive.

01:17:01.910 --> 01:17:04.670
But I think it's seen
as practical

01:17:04.670 --> 01:17:06.290
here, rather than intrusive.

01:17:09.710 --> 01:17:11.280
It doesn't help, I know.

01:17:11.280 --> 01:17:17.055
AUDIENCE: Yeah, because during
talk, you said that during

01:17:17.055 --> 01:17:21.860
business events, you should
apply some of those Swiss

01:17:21.860 --> 01:17:22.720
rules, right?

01:17:22.720 --> 01:17:25.990
To not bring our humor on
the table, et cetera.

01:17:25.990 --> 01:17:29.930
But now, I hear that when
there's a business event, some

01:17:29.930 --> 01:17:31.095
rules might be broken.

01:17:31.095 --> 01:17:33.090
DICCON BEWES: Well, yeah,
but you're not the one

01:17:33.090 --> 01:17:33.880
breaking the rules.

01:17:33.880 --> 01:17:34.790
That's the thing.

01:17:34.790 --> 01:17:37.460
If you then turn around to your
prospective landlord and

01:17:37.460 --> 01:17:41.375
say, well actually, are you
married or do you have a

01:17:41.375 --> 01:17:43.362
boyfriend or whatever, he would
probably not take too

01:17:43.362 --> 01:17:45.722
kindly to that.

01:17:45.722 --> 01:17:48.350
So different rules apply
in terms of status.

01:17:48.350 --> 01:17:50.590
AUDIENCE: The nature of
my question was how to

01:17:50.590 --> 01:17:51.560
distinguish, right?

01:17:51.560 --> 01:17:53.970
We, as foreigners,
how to behave.

01:17:53.970 --> 01:17:54.760
That was the meat
of the question.

01:17:54.760 --> 01:17:57.220
DICCON BEWES: I think the best
advice, really, is behave the

01:17:57.220 --> 01:17:59.490
way the people around
you are behaving.

01:17:59.490 --> 01:18:02.780
If your boss and your colleagues
almost never make

01:18:02.780 --> 01:18:07.160
jokes in meetings, then the idea
is don't make a joke in

01:18:07.160 --> 01:18:07.520
the meeting.

01:18:07.520 --> 01:18:09.720
AUDIENCE: And still protect
your fruit.

01:18:09.720 --> 01:18:12.560
DICCON BEWES: Well, I've really
developed a thick skin,

01:18:12.560 --> 01:18:15.456
become a little bit
more of a coconut.

01:18:15.456 --> 01:18:17.424
Turn from a peach
to a coconut.

01:18:17.424 --> 01:18:19.884
Become a hairy peach.

01:18:19.884 --> 01:18:22.590
It is difficult, and it's one
of the hardest things about

01:18:22.590 --> 01:18:26.580
integrating here is keeping
your own sense of self and

01:18:26.580 --> 01:18:28.290
your own culture but
also fitting in.

